{"title_page": "Manchester Arena bombing", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 suicide bombing}}\n{{about|the 2017 suicide bombing|the IRA bombing in 1996|1996 Manchester bombing|other bombings|Manchester bombing (disambiguation){{!}}Manchester bombing}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| map              = {{Location map many | Greater Manchester#United Kingdom\n| width        = 280\n| float        = centre\n| label        = Manchester Arena\n| position     = right\n| background   = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|53|29|17.3|N|2|14|34|W}}\n}}\n| partof           = [[Islamic terrorism in Europe]]\n| image            = Manchester Arena exterior, (3) May19.jpg\n| image_size       = 300px\n| alt              = \n| caption          = [[Manchester Arena]] in 2019\n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = File:Manchester bombing.png\n| map_caption      = \n| title            = \n| location         = [[Manchester Arena]],<br />[[Manchester]], England\n| target           = Concert-goers\n| coordinates      = {{coord|53|29|17.3|N|2|14|34|W|display=inline,title}}\n| date             = {{start date and age|2017|05|22|df=yes}}\n| time             = 22:31<!--NOT 22:33. That's when the first emergency calls were made.-->\n| timezone         = [[British Summer Time|BST]]\n| weapon           = [[Acetone peroxide|TATP]] [[nail bomb]]\n| type             = [[Suicide bombing]]\n| fatalities       = 23 (including the perpetrator) <!--Consensus is to phrase this along the lines of \"23, including the attacker\", as opposed to \"22, excluding the attacker\".-->\n| injuries         = 800+<ref name=\"800Injured\"/><br />Hospitalised: 112<ref>{{cite web |title=Elite sports centre to treat bomb victims |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-43455692 |website=BBC News |date=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n| victims          = \n| perpetrators     = Salman & Hashem Abedi<ref>{{Cite news|title=Manchester Arena bombing: Hashem Abedi guilty of 22 murders|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-51926162|publisher=BBC News|date=17 Mar 2020|access-date=17 Mar 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| motive           = [[Islamic extremism]]<ref name=\"MayJune04\"/>\n| numparts         = \n| dfens            = \n| inquiry          = \n| coroner          = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module           = \n}}\nOn 22 May 2017, an [[Islamic extremism|Islamic extremist]] [[suicide bombing attack|suicide bomber]] detonated a [[nail bomb|shrapnel-laden]] [[homemade bomb]] as people were leaving the [[Manchester Arena]], England following [[Dangerous Woman Tour|a concert]] by the American singer [[Ariana Grande]].\n\nTwenty-three<!-- Consensus is to phrase this along the lines of \"23, including the attacker\", as opposed to \"22, excluding the attacker\" --> people died, including the attacker, and 139 were wounded, more than half of them children. Several hundred more suffered [[psychological trauma]]. The bomber was Salman Ramadan Abedi, a 22-year-old local man of Libyan ancestry. After initial suspicions of a terrorist network, police later said they believed Abedi had largely acted alone but that others had been aware of his plans. In March 2020, the bomber's brother, Hashem Abedi, was found guilty of 22 counts of murder in relation to the attack.\n\nThe incident was the deadliest terrorist attack and the first suicide bombing in the United Kingdom since the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]].\n\n==Attack==\nOn 22 May 2017 at 22:31<!-- NOT 22:33. That's when the first emergency calls were made. --> [[British Summer Time|BST]] ([[UTC+01:00]]),<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|3.8}} a [[Suicide bombing|suicide bomber]] detonated an improvised explosive device, [[Nail bomb|packed with nuts and bolts to act as shrapnel]], in the [[foyer]] area of the [[Manchester Arena]]. The attack took place after an Ariana Grande concert that was part of her 2017 [[Dangerous Woman Tour]].<ref name=\"BBCconfirm2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40007886|title=Manchester Arena blast: 19 dead and more than 50 hurt|date=22 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|access-date=22 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522223115/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40007886|archivedate=22 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/ariana-grande-concert-manchester-arena-explosion/|title=UK police: 22 confirmed dead after terror incident at Ariana Grande concert|publisher=[[CBSN|CBS News]]|date=22 May 2017|access-date=22 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523062040/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/ariana-grande-concert-manchester-arena-explosion/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> 14,200 people attended the concert.<ref>{{cite news|title=Manchester One Love concert: 'Thousands make false ticket claims'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40118865|publisher=BBC News|date=1 June 2017|access-date=1 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601150506/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40118865|archivedate=1 June 2017}}</ref> Many exiting concert-goers and waiting parents were in the foyer at the time of the explosion. According to evidence presented at the [[Coroner (England and Wales)|coroner's inquest]], the bomb was strong enough to kill people up to {{convert|20|m|ft}} away.<ref name=\"inquest\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/09/manchester-arena-bomb-designed-kill-largest-number-innocents|title=Manchester Arena bomb was designed to kill largest number of innocents|last=Pidd|first=Helen|date=9 June 2017|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=10 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610042404/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/09/manchester-arena-bomb-designed-kill-largest-number-innocents|archivedate=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Greater Manchester Police]] declared the incident a terrorist attack and [[suicide bombing]]. It was the deadliest attack in the United Kingdom since the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]].<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|3}}\n\n===Aftermath===\nAbout three hours after the bombing, police conducted a [[controlled explosion]] on a suspicious item of clothing in [[Cathedral Gardens]]. This was later confirmed to have been abandoned clothing and not dangerous.<ref name=\"BBC-attack-23-05-2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40010124|title=Manchester Arena attack: 22 dead and 59 hurt|publisher=BBC News|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523061202/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40010124|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/23/isis-claim-responsibility-for-the-manchester-attack-that-killed-22-6655764/|title=Isis claim responsibility for the Manchester attack that killed 22.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523131922/http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/23/isis-claim-responsibility-for-the-manchester-attack-that-killed-22-6655764/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nResidents and taxi companies in Manchester offered free transport or accommodation via Twitter to those left stranded at the concert.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|4.85}} Parents were separated from their children attending the concert in the aftermath of the explosion. A nearby hotel served as a shelter for people displaced by the bombing, with officials directing separated parents and children there.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|4.85}} Manchester's [[Sikhism|Sikh]] temples ([[gurdwara]]s) along with local homeowners, hotels and venues offered shelter to survivors of the attack.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pells|first1=Rachael|title=Manchester Sikh temples offer food and shelter to people affected by terror attack|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-sikh-temples-food-shelter-people-terror-attack-suicide-bomb-harinder-kukreja-gurdwara-a7750881.html|accessdate=25 May 2017|work=[[The Independent]]|date=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523131036/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-sikh-temples-food-shelter-people-terror-attack-suicide-bomb-harinder-kukreja-gurdwara-a7750881.html|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Operation Temperer May 2017 (1).jpg|thumb|British military personnel alongside armed police as part of [[Operation Temperer]] in response to the raised threat level<!-- No full stop. See MOS:CAPFRAG -->]]\n[[Manchester Victoria station|Manchester Victoria railway station]], which is partly underneath the arena, was evacuated and closed, and services were cancelled.<ref name=\"BBCconfirm2\"/><ref name=\"abc\">{{Cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/police-respond-reports-incident-manchester-arena/story?id=47569092|title=Deaths, injuries after reports of explosion at Ariana Grande concert at Manchester Arena: Police|date=22 May 2017|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=22 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523013947/http://abcnews.go.com/International/police-respond-reports-incident-manchester-arena/story?id=47569092|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> The explosion caused structural damage to the station, which remained closed until the damage had been assessed and repaired, resulting in disruption to train and tram services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Structural damage to Victoria Station after bomb|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-26/structural-damage-to-victoria-station-after-bomb/|publisher=[[itv.com|ITV]] News|accessdate=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527131405/http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-26/structural-damage-to-victoria-station-after-bomb/|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref> The station reopened to traffic eight days later, following the completion of police investigation work and repairs to the fabric of the building.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|4.57}}\n\nAfter a [[Civil Contingencies Committee|COBRA]] meeting with [[Greater Manchester Police|Greater Manchester's Chief Constable]], [[Ian Hopkins]], on 23 May, Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] announced that the UK's [[UK Threat Levels|terror threat level]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mi5.gov.uk/threat-levels |title=Threat Levels |website=Security \\service \u2013 [[MI5]] |accessdate=26 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525220445/https://www.mi5.gov.uk/threat-levels |archivedate=25 May 2017  }} Threat levels in Great Britain and in Northern Ireland from international and Northern Ireland-related terrorism, published here, are deemed \"critical\" for a period following the attack.</ref> was raised to \"critical\", its highest level.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|5.247}} The threat level remained critical until 27 May, when it was reduced to its previous level of severe.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40069959 |title=Manchester attack: Terror threat reduced from critical to severe |publisher=BBC News |date=27 May 2017 |accessdate=27 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527101510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40069959 |archivedate=27 May 2017  }}</ref> In the aftermath of the attack [[Operation Temperer]] was activated for the first time, allowing up to 5,000 soldiers to reinforce armed police in protecting parts of the country.<ref name=\"ITV News threat level 2017\">{{cite news |title=PM Theresa May raises UK threat level to 'critical' |website=ITV News |date=23 May 2017 |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-05-23/uk-threat-level-raised-to-critical-severe/ |access-date=23 May 2017 |quote=Raising the level to critical means that military personnel could be deployed to support armed police officers \u2013 part of a plan known as Operation Temperer. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523215312/http://www.itv.com/news/2017-05-23/uk-threat-level-raised-to-critical-severe/ |archivedate=23 May 2017  }}</ref><ref name=\"alan travis temperer twitter\">{{cite tweet |first=Alan |last=Travis |retweet=The Guardian |user=alantravis40 |number=867119049028890624 |date=23 May 2017 |title=PM says Critical Threat level's Operation Temperer will use up to 5,000 troops to take over armed police patrol duties under police command.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40068803/manchester-attack-pm-says-terror-threat-level-reduced-from-critical|access-date=27 May 2017|title=Manchester attack: PM says terror threat level reduced from critical|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530171831/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40068803/manchester-attack-pm-says-terror-threat-level-reduced-from-critical|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> Tours of the [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]] and the [[Changing the Queen's Life Guard|Changing of the Guard]] ceremony at [[Buckingham Palace]] were cancelled on 24 May, and troops were deployed to guard government buildings in London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi.html|title=3 Men Arrested in Investigation of Manchester Bombing|last=Bennhold|first=Katrin|date=24 May 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=24 May 2017|last2=Castle|first2=Stephen|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524151028/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi.html|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 May, the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]], via the Nashir [[Telegram (messaging service)|Telegram]] channel, claimed the attack was carried out by \"a soldier of the [[Khilafah]]\". The message called the attack \"an endeavor to terrorize the [[mushrik]]in, and in response to their transgressions against the lands of the Muslims.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/23/world/europe/manchester-arena-attack-ariana-grande.html| title=ISIS Claims Responsibility for Manchester Concert Attack; Toll Rises to 22|date=23 May 2017|work=The New York Times|last2=Erlanger|first2=Steven|last1=Yeginsu|first1=Ceylan|accessdate=23 May 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523083054/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/23/world/europe/manchester-arena-attack-ariana-grande.html| archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://time.com/4790201/isis-manchester-concert-terrorist-attack/|title=ISIS Claims Responsibility For Manchester Concert Terrorist Attack|date=23 May 2017|work=Time|last1=Samuelson|first1=Kate|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523125036/http://time.com/4790201/isis-manchester-concert-terrorist-attack/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-arena-attack-isis-responsible-claim-suicide-bombing-islamic-state-ariana-grande-concert-a7751221.html|title=Isis has claimed responsibility for the Manchester Arena attack|date=23 May 2017|work=The Independent|last1=Dearden|first1=Lizzie|accessdate=23 May 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523121220/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-arena-attack-isis-responsible-claim-suicide-bombing-islamic-state-ariana-grande-concert-a7751221.html| archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi's sister said that he was motivated by revenge for Muslim children killed by [[American-led intervention in Syria|American airstrikes in Syria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/25/salman-abedi-wanted-revenge-us-air-strikes-syriamanchester-bombers| title=Salman Abedi 'wanted revenge' for US air strikes in Syria,&nbsp;Manchester bomber's sister says|work=The Telegraph|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525050239/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/25/salman-abedi-wanted-revenge-us-air-strikes-syriamanchester-bombers/|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/manchester-bomber-fought-in-libya-1495662073|title=Manchester Bomber Believed Muslims Were Mistreated, Sought Revenge|last=Morajea|first=Hassan|date=25 May 2017|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|last2=Kantchev|first2=Georgi|issn=0099-9660|last3=Bird| first3=Mike|last4=Gold|first4=Riva|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524214833/https://www.wsj.com/articles/manchester-bomber-fought-in-libya-1495662073|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Arena remained closed until September 2017, with scheduled concerts either cancelled or moved to other venues.<ref name=\"concerts\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40275744| title=Manchester Arena to stay closed until September|publisher=BBC News|date=14 June 2017|accessdate=14 June 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614122402/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40275744|archivedate=14 June 2017}}</ref> It reopened on 9 September, with a benefit concert featuring [[Noel Gallagher]] and other acts associated with [[North West England]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40943849 |title=Manchester Arena: Noel Gallagher to headline reopening concert |publisher=BBC News |date=16 August 2017 |accessdate=16 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816071206/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40943849 |archivedate=16 August 2017  }}</ref>\n\nMay announced an extra \u00a313 million reimbursement from central government to Manchester's public services for most of the costs incurred by the attack in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-42808483 |title=Manchester Arena attack: Theresa May announces payout package |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=24 January 2018 |accessdate=24 January 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124202311/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-42808483 |archivedate=24 January 2018  }}</ref> Later that month, Chris Parker, a homeless man who stole from victims of the attack, was jailed for 4 years and three months.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-42876790| title=Manchester Arena attack 'hero' jailed for theft|work=BBC News|date=30 January 2018|accessdate=30 January 2018|url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130135828/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-42876790|archivedate=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\n<!-- NO LIST OF VICTIMS PLEASE PER TALK PAGE CONSENSUS: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:2017_Manchester_Arena_bombing/Archive_2#RfC:_Should_the_victims_be_named.3F --><!--NOTE: there were TWENTYTHREE dead, 22 victims and the bomber. It's not correct to speak of 22 dead people. 22 concert-goers, or victims; 23 people.-->\nThe blast killed the attacker and 22<!-- Consensus is to phrase this along the lines of \"23, including the attacker\", as opposed to \"22, excluding the attacker\". --> concert-goers and parents who were in the entrance waiting to pick up their children following the show; 119 people were initially reported as injured.<ref name=\"Metro.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/23/12-children-under-16-are-among-manchester-terror-attack-injured-6655858/|title=Twelve children under 16 are among Manchester terror attack injured|last=Metro.co.uk|first=Nicole Morley for|date=23 May 2017|website=Metro|url-status=live|access-date=29 May 2017|quote=22 people have been killed and 59 were taken to hospital following the blast. 119 people were injured in total.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523154239/http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/23/12-children-under-16-are-among-manchester-terror-attack-injured-6655858/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GdnSing\" /> This number was revised by police to 250 on 22 June, with the addition of severe [[psychological trauma]] and minor injuries.<ref name=\"250Injured\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/number-people-injured-manchester-arena-13223904|title=Number of people injured in Manchester terror attack rises to 250|last=Abbit|first=Beth|date=22 June 2017|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|access-date=26 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622155426/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/number-people-injured-manchester-arena-13223904|archivedate=22 June 2017}}</ref> In May 2018, the number of injured was revised to 800.<ref name=\"800Injured\">{{cite web|title=Arena bomb 'injured more than 800'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-44129386|website=BBC News|accessdate=16 May 2018|date=16 May 2018}}</ref> The dead included ten people aged under 20; the youngest victim was an eight-year-old girl and the oldest was a 51-year-old woman.<ref name=\"GdnSing\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/go-sing-with-the-angels-families-and-friends-pay-tribute-to-manchester-victims|title=Go sing with the angels: families pay tribute to Manchester victims|last=Topping|first=Alexandra|date=24 May 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525171256/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/go-sing-with-the-angels-families-and-friends-pay-tribute-to-manchester-victims|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> Of the 22 victims, twenty were [[Briton]]s and two were British-based Polish nationals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-victims-named-dead-terror--13080028|first=Alex|last=Pesic|title=These are the 22 victims of the Manchester Arena terror attack|date=29 May 2017|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|accessdate=14 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616133649/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-victims-named-dead-terror--13080028|archivedate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[North West Ambulance Service]] reported that 60 of its ambulances attended the scene, carried 59 people to local hospitals, and treated [[walking wounded]] on site.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|2}} Of those hospitalised, 12 were children under the age of 16.<ref name=\"Metro.uk\" />  In total, 112 people were hospitalized for their injuries, and 27 were treated for injuries that did not require hospitalization.  Out of this total of 139, 79 were children.<ref name=\"GdnExdradit\"/>\n\nThe first doctor thought to have been on scene was an off-duty consultant anaesthetist, Michael Daley.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gulland|first=Anne|date=30 June 2017|title=Doctors commended for their bravery in response to terrorist incidents|url=http://www.bmj.com/content/357/bmj.j3184|journal=BMJ|volume=357|pages=j3184|doi=10.1136/bmj.j3184|issn=0959-8138|pmid=28667098|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630171447/http://www.bmj.com/content/357/bmj.j3184|archivedate=30 June 2017}}</ref> In recognition of his bravery for the role he played in the immediate medical response to the incident, Daley's name was entered into the [[British Medical Association]] Book of Valour in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/about-us/who-we-are/awards-and-honours|title=BMA \u2013 Awards and honours|website=bma.org.uk|accessdate=3 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730023412/https://www.bma.org.uk/about-us/who-we-are/awards-and-honours|archivedate=30 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Attacker==\n<!--DO NOT ADD ANY INFOBOXES WITHOUT FIRST CONSULTING THE TALK PAGE -->\nThe bomber, Salman Ramadan Abedi, was a 22-year-old British Muslim of Libyan ancestry.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web |first1=Martin |last1=Evans |first2=Victoria |last2=Ward |first3=Robert |last3=Mendick |first4=Ben |last4=Farmer |first5=Hayley |last5=Dixon |first6=Danny |last6=Boyle |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/everything-know-salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber/ |title=Everything we know about Salman Abedi, the Manchester suicide bomber |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=26 May 2017 |accessdate=26 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525235330/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/everything-know-salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber/ |archivedate=25 May 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/manchester-bombing-attack-salman-abedi-teenage-aggression-family-614358|title=The Manchester bomber was a promising young man who went off the rails, says a religious leader who knew him|last=Paton|first=Callum|date=23 May 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524195149/http://www.newsweek.com/manchester-bombing-attack-salman-abedi-teenage-aggression-family-614358|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> He was born in Manchester on 31 December 1994 to a [[Salafism|Salafi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/story/the-manchester-bomber-grew-up-in-a-neighborhood-struggling-with-extremism|title=The Manchester bomber grew up in a neighborhood struggling with extremism|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525190723/https://news.vice.com/story/the-manchester-bomber-grew-up-in-a-neighborhood-struggling-with-extremism|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> family of Libyan-born refugees who had settled in south Manchester after fleeing to the UK to escape the government of [[Muammar Gaddafi]]. He had two brothers and a sister.<ref name=\"who was salman abedi\">{{cite news|title=Manchester attack: Who was Salman Abedi?|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-40019135|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524072701/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-40019135|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber-know/|title=Salman Abedi named as the Manchester suicide bomber \u2013 what we know about him|last1=Evans|first1=Martin|last2=Ward|first2=Victoria|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=23 May 2017|quote=his parents were Libyan refugees who came to the UK to escape the Gaddafi regime|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523180222/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber-know/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> He grew up in the [[Whalley Range, Manchester|Whalley Range]] area and lived in [[Fallowfield]].<ref name=\"telegrsalman\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber-know/|title=Salman Abedi named as the Manchester suicide bomber \u2013 what we know about him|last1=Evans|first1=Martin|last2=Ward|first2=Victoria|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523180222/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber-know/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> Neighbours described the Abedi family as very traditional and \"super religious\".<ref>Connor, Richard (25 May 2017). [http://www.dw.com/en/manchester-bomber-a-life-on-the-move/a-38979272 Manchester bomber: A life on the move.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530111613/http://www.dw.com/en/manchester-bomber-a-life-on-the-move/a-38979272 |date=30 May 2017 }} Deutsche Welle. Retrieved 26 May 2017.</ref> Abedi, his elder brother,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/world/europe/92911194/the-face-of-hate-manchester-arena-attack-suspect-salman-abedis-home-raided  |title=The face of hate': Manchester Arena attack suspect Salman Abedi's home raided, disturbing book found |date =24 May 2017 |publisher=Stuff}}</ref> and, prior to 2011, his father attended [[Didsbury Mosque]].<ref name=\"telegrsalman\" /><ref name=\"guardmosque\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ian Cobain|last2=Frances Perraudin|last3=Steven Morris|last4=Nazia Parveen|title=Salman Ramadan Abedi named by police as Manchester Arena attacker|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|accessdate=27 May 2017|work=The Guardian|quote=Salman and his brother Ismail worshipped at Didsbury mosque, where their father, who is known as Abu Ismail within the community, is a well-known figure. \"He used to do the five and call the adhan. He has an absolutely beautiful voice. And his boys learned the Qur'an by heart.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526212713/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|archivedate=26 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi attended [[Wellacre Academy|Wellacre Technology College]], [[Burnage Academy for Boys]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Devine |first1=Peter |title=Manchester Arena bomber Salman Abedi was former Wellacre pupil |url=https://www.messengernewspapers.co.uk/news/whereyoulive/15321454.manchester-arena-bomber-salman-abedi-was-former-wellacre-pupil/ |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=Messenger Newspapers |date=1 June 2017}}</ref> and [[The Manchester College]]. A former tutor remarked that Abedi was \"a very slow, uneducated and passive person\".<ref name=GMay26/> According to ''[[The Times]]'', Abedi had been among a group of students at his high school who had accused a teacher of [[Islamophobia]] for asking them what they thought of suicide bombers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dearden|first1=Lizzie|title=Salman Abedi once called RE teacher an 'Islamophobe' for asking his opinion of suicide bombers|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salman-abedi-re-teacher-islamophobe-suicide-bombers-burnage-academy-for-boys-opinion-manchester-a7756611.html|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=The Independent|date=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606082916/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salman-abedi-re-teacher-islamophobe-suicide-bombers-burnage-academy-for-boys-opinion-manchester-a7756611.html|archivedate=6 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Simpson|first1=John|last2=Gibbons|first2=Katie|last3=Kenber|first3=Billy|last4=Trew|first4=Bel|title=Abedi called teacher an Islamophobe|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/killer-called-teacher-an-islamophobe-v9tgnkxd0|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=[[The Times]]|date=26 May 2017}}</ref> He also reportedly said to his friends that being a suicide bomber 'was ok' and fellow college students raised concerns about his behaviour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-banned-13092209|title=Salman Abedi banned from mosque and reported to authorities for extremist views|last=Fox|first=Aine|date=25 May 2017|work=Manchester Evening News|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAbedi's father was a member of the [[Libyan Islamic Fighting Group]], a Salafi jihadist organisation proscribed by the United Nations,<ref name=\"un1267\">{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sc/committees/1267/NSQE01101E.shtml |title=QE.L.11.01. Libyan Islamic Fighting Group |publisher=[[United Nations Security Council Al-Qaida Sanctions Committee]] |date=23 August 2010 |accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref> and father and son fought for the group in Libya in 2011 as part of the movement to [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|overthrow Muammar Gaddafi]].<ref name=GMay26>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/26/salman-abedi-manchester-arena-attack-partying-suicide-bomber Salman Abedi: from hot-headed party lover to suicide bomber]. ''The Guardian'' (26 May 2017). Retrieved 2018-10-26.</ref> Abedi's parents, both born in [[Tripoli]], remained in Libya in 2011,<ref name=\"telegrsalman\" /> while 17-year-old Abedi returned to live in the United Kingdom. He took a [[gap year]] in 2014, where he returned with his brother Hashem to Libya to live with his parents. Abedi was injured in [[Ajdabiya]] that year while fighting for an Islamist group.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/28/salman-abedi-manchester-arena-bomber-radicalisation How Manchester bomber Salman Abedi was radicalised by his links to Libya]. ''The Guardian'' (27 May 2017). Retrieved 2018-10-26.</ref> The brothers were rescued from Tripoli by the [[Royal Navy]] survey ship {{HMS|Enterprise|H88|6}} in August 2014 as part of a group of 110 British citizens as the [[Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|Libyan civil war]] erupted, taken to [[Malta]] and flown back to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/royal-navy-rescued-manchester-bomber-from-the-libyan-civil-war-11454899|title=Manchester bomber Salman Abedi was rescued from Libyan civil war by Royal Navy|work=[[Sky News]]|date=31 July 2018|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-45021513|title=Did MI5 miss chance to catch Manchester Arena bomber Salman Abedi?|work=[[BBC News]]|date=31 July 2018|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> According to a retired European intelligence officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, Abedi met with members of the ISIS Battar brigade in [[Sabratha]], Libya and continued to be in contact with the group upon his return to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Rukmini|last1=Callimachi|first2=Eric|last2=Schmit|title=Manchester bomber met with ISIS unit in Libya, officials say|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/03/world/middleeast/manchester-bombing-salman-abedi-islamic-state-libya.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 June 2017|accessdate=4 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603225742/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/03/world/middleeast/manchester-bombing-salman-abedi-islamic-state-libya.html|archivedate=3 June 2017}}</ref> An [[imam]] at Didsbury mosque recalled that Abedi looked at him \"with hate\" after he preached against [[ISIS]] and [[Ansar al-Sharia (Libya)|Ansar al-Sharia]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cobain|first1=Ian|last2=Perraudin|first2=Frances|last3=Morris|first3=Steven|last4=Parveen|first4=Nazia|title=Salman Ramadan Abedi named by police as Manchester Arena attacker|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|accessdate=24 May 2017|work=The Guardian|date=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524003525/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an acquaintance in the UK, Abedi was \"outgoing\" and consumed alcohol,<ref name=cannabis>{{Cite news|title=Salman Abedi: How Manchester attacker turned from cannabis-smoking dropout to Isis suicide bomber|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salman-abedi-manchester-attacker-isis-terrorist-europe-islamist-suicide-bomber-arena-explosion-a7753541.html|last=Dearden|first=Lizzie|date=24 May 2017|work=The Independent|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819204355/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salman-abedi-manchester-attacker-isis-terrorist-europe-islamist-suicide-bomber-arena-explosion-a7753541.html|archivedate=19 August 2017}}</ref> while another said that Abedi was a \"regular kid who went out and drank\" until about 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everything we know about Salman Abedi, the Manchester suicide bomber|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/everything-know-salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525235330/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/everything-know-salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber/|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi was also known to have used cannabis.<ref name=\"who was salman abedi\" /><ref name=\"cannabis\" />  He enrolled at the [[University of Salford]] in September 2014, where he studied [[business administration]], before dropping out to work in a [[bakery]].<ref name=\"who was salman abedi\" /> Manchester police believe Abedi used [[student loan]]s to finance the plot, including travel overseas to learn bomb-making.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robert Mendick|last2=Martin Evans|last3=Victoria Ward|title=Exclusive: Manchester suicide bomber used student loan and benefits to fund terror plot|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/26/exclusive-manchester-suicide-bomber-used-student-loan-benefits/|accessdate=27 May 2017|work=The Telegraph|quote=The Manchester suicide bomber used taxpayer-funded student loans and benefits to bankroll the terror plot, police believe.  Salman Abedi is understood to have received thousands of pounds in state funding in the run up to Monday's atrocity even while he was overseas receiving bomb-making training.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527010434/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/26/exclusive-manchester-suicide-bomber-used-student-loan-benefits/|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that despite dropping out from further education, he continued to receive student loan funding as recently as April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ian Cobain|last2=Ewen MacAskill|title=Police focus on Libya amid reports of arrest of Salman Abedi's brother|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/manchester-attack-police-focus-on-libya-as-salman-abedi-brother-arrested|accessdate=27 May 2017|work=The Guardian|quote=Abedi studied business and management at Salford University two or three years ago, but dropped out of the course and did not complete his degree. The Guardian understands he was receiving student loan payments as recently as last month.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527033654/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/manchester-attack-police-focus-on-libya-as-salman-abedi-brother-arrested|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi returned to Manchester on 18 May after a trip to Libya and bought bomb-making material, apparently constructing the [[acetone peroxide]]-based bomb by himself. It is known that many members of the ISIS Battar brigade trained people in bomb-making in Libya.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lizzie|last=Dearden|title=Manchester attack: Salman Abedi 'made bomb in four days' after potentially undergoing terror training in Libya|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-attack-bombing-salman-abedi-isis-libya-terror-training-militants-tatp-four-days-bomb-a7771391.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|location=London|date=3 June 2017|accessdate=4 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603185354/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-attack-bombing-salman-abedi-isis-libya-terror-training-militants-tatp-four-days-bomb-a7771391.html|archivedate=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was known to British security services and police but was not regarded as a high risk, having been linked to petty crime but never flagged up for radical views.<ref name=\"guardmosque\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|title=Manchester Arena attacker named by police as Salman Ramadan Abedi|work=The Guardian|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523174251/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/police-reveal-manchester-attacker-salman-abedi-s-petty-criminal-past/story-iALPPyhtag37nTFGbchxhL.html|title=Police reveal Manchester attacker Salman Abedi's petty criminal past|date=30 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530191618/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/police-reveal-manchester-attacker-salman-abedi-s-petty-criminal-past/story-iALPPyhtag37nTFGbchxhL.html|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> A community worker told the BBC he had called a hotline five years before the bombing to warn police about Abedi's views and members of Britain's [[Libyan diaspora]] said they had \"warned authorities for years\" about Manchester's [[Islamism in the United Kingdom|Islamist]] [[radicalisation]].<ref name=\"bbc2504\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stephen|first1=Chris|title=Libyans in UK 'warned about Manchester radicalisation for years'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/libyans-in-uk-warned-about-manchester-radicalisation-for-years|accessdate=25 May 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524222943/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/libyans-in-uk-warned-about-manchester-radicalisation-for-years|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi was allegedly reported to authorities for his [[extremism]] by five community leaders and family members and had been banned from a mosque;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/security-services-missed-five-opportunities-stop-manchester/|title=Security services missed five opportunities to stop the Manchester bomber|newspaper=The Telegraph|first1=Robert|last1=Mendick|first2=Gordon|last2=Rayner|first3=Martin|last3=Evans|first4=Hayley|last4=Dixon|date=25 May 2017|access-date=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526021047/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/security-services-missed-five-opportunities-stop-manchester/|archivedate=26 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sharman|first1=Jon|title=Manchester attack: Members of the public 'reported Salman Abedi to anti-terror hotline'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-attack-latest-public-reported-salman-abedi-terrorism-hotline-a7754621.html|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=[[The Independent]]|date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525031417/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-attack-latest-public-reported-salman-abedi-terrorism-hotline-a7754621.html|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fox|first1=Aine|last2=Abbit|first2=Beth|title=Manchester bomber Salman Abedi was banned from a mosque and reported to authorities for his extremist views|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-banned-13092209|date=25 May 2017|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=Manchester Evening News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525161030/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-banned-13092209|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> the [[Chief Constable of Greater Manchester]], though, said Abedi was not known to the [[CONTEST#Prevent|Prevent]] anti-radicalisation programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/30/salman-abedi-unknown-prevent-workers-manchester-police|title=Salman Abedi was unknown to Prevent workers, says police chief|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|work=The Guardian|date=30 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530191024/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/30/salman-abedi-unknown-prevent-workers-manchester-police|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2017, [[MI5]] launched an internal inquiry into its handling of the warnings it had received about Abedi and a second, \"more in depth\" inquiry, into how it missed the danger.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/05/29/europe/mi5-internal-inquiry-abedi/ |title=MI5 launches internal inquiry over Manchester bomber warnings |publisher=CNN |date=29 May 2017 |accessdate=29 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605115324/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/05/29/europe/mi5-internal-inquiry-abedi |archivedate=5 June 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-40080646 |title=Manchester attacks: MI5 probes bomber 'warnings' |publisher=BBC News |date=29 May 2017 |accessdate=29 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529065526/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-40080646 |archivedate=29 May 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/28/mi5-launches-inquiries-into-failings-on-manchester-arena-bomber-salman-abedi-moss-side-raids-amber-rudd|title=MI5 opens inquiries into missed warnings over Manchester terror threat|last=Dodd|first=Vikram|date=29 May 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530172400/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/28/mi5-launches-inquiries-into-failings-on-manchester-arena-bomber-salman-abedi-moss-side-raids-amber-rudd|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> The ''Daily Mail'' reported that MI5 had a policy of allowing Libyans in the UK to travel to fight against Gaddafi and return later, including some who had been under house arrest in the UK for counter-terrorist measures.<ref>Curtis, Mark (5 April 2018). [https://www.middleeasteye.net/columns/what-will-be-blowback-uk-government-after-libya-revelations-1624802462 What will be the blowback for UK government after Libya revelations?]. Middle East Eye. Retrieved 2018-10-26.</ref> On 22 November 2018, the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament]] published a report which said that MI5 had acted \"too slowly\" in its dealings with Abedi. The committee's report noted \"What we can say is that there were a number of a failings in the handling of Salman Abedi's case. While it is impossible to say whether these would have prevented the devastating attack on 22 May, we have concluded that as a result of the failings, potential opportunities to prevent it were missed.\"<ref name=\"BBCreport\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46303812|title=MI5 'too slow' over Manchester Arena bomber|date=22 November 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Manchester bombing.png|thumb|350px|Bombing location map<!-- No period&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;see MOS:CAPFRAG -->]]\nThe property in Fallowfield where Abedi lived was raided on 23 May. Armed police breached the house with a controlled explosion and searched it. Abedi's 23-year-old brother was arrested in [[Chorlton-cum-Hardy]] in south Manchester in relation to the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-attack-bombing-suspect-named-as-salman-abedi-us-officials-say-a3546576.html|title=Manchester attack: Bombing suspect named as Salman Abedi, police confirm|last=Simpson|first=Fiona|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|location=London|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523173941/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-attack-bombing-suspect-named-as-salman-abedi-us-officials-say-a3546576.html|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"FT-bomber-named\" /> Police carried out raids in two other areas of south Manchester and another address in the Whalley Range area.<ref name=\"FT-bomber-named\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/59ee15dc-3fc5-11e7-82b6-896b95f30f58|title=Manchester suicide bomber named as 22-year-old from city|first1=Sam|last1=Jones|first2=Leila|last2=Haddou|first3=Andrew|last3=Bounds|work=[[Financial Times]]|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606204257/https://www.ft.com/content/59ee15dc-3fc5-11e7-82b6-896b95f30f58|archivedate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Three other men were arrested, and police initially spoke of a network supporting the bomber;<ref name=bbc2504>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40032504|title=Manchester attack: Police hunt 'network' behind bomber|publisher=BBC News|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524144125/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40032504|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> they later announced that Abedi had sourced all the bomb components himself, and that they now believed he had largely acted alone.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/31/police-believe-manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-acted-largely-alone|title=Police believe Manchester bomber Salman Abedi largely acted alone|last=Pidd|first=Helen|date=31 May 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|issn=0261-3077|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531010801/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/31/police-believe-manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-acted-largely-alone|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref> On 6 July, police said that they believed others had been aware of Abedi's plans.<ref name=\"Gdn7717\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jul/06/manchester-bombing-police-believe-salman-abedi-did-not-act-alone|title=Manchester bombing: police say Salman Abedi did not act alone|last=Parveen|first=Nazia|date=7 July 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707012340/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jul/06/manchester-bombing-police-believe-salman-abedi-did-not-act-alone|archivedate=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to German police sources, Abedi transited through [[D\u00fcsseldorf Airport]] on his way home to Manchester from Istanbul four days before the bombing.<ref>{{cite news |last=Huggler |first=Justin |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/25/manchester-bomber-dusseldorf-four-days-attack-german-media-reports/ |title=Manchester bomber passed through Dusseldorf four days before the attack, German media reports |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 May 2017 |accessdate=30 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530061033/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/25/manchester-bomber-dusseldorf-four-days-attack-german-media-reports/ |archivedate=30 May 2017  }}</ref> French interior minister [[G\u00e9rard Collomb]] said in an interview with [[BFM TV]] that Abedi may have been to Syria, and had \"proven\" links with ISIS.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/french-interior-minister-salman-abedi-had-proven-links-with-islamic-state/|first=Saim|last=Saeed|title=French interior minister: Salman Abedi had 'proven' links with Islamic State|work=[[politico.eu]]|date=24 May 2017|access-date=1 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524124439/http://www.politico.eu/article/french-interior-minister-salman-abedi-had-proven-links-with-islamic-state/|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi's younger brother and father were arrested by [[RADA Special Deterrence Forces|Libyan security forces]] on 23 and 24 May respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-security-manchester-libya-idUSKBN18K28M?il=0|title=Manchester bomber's father says he did not expect attack|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=25 May 2017|access-date=29 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524214731/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-security-manchester-libya-idUSKBN18K28M?il=0|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> The brother was suspected of planning an attack in Libya, and was said to be in regular touch with Salman, and aware of the plan to bomb the Manchester Arena,<ref name=\"WaPo-24-05-2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/british-prime-minister-raises-nations-threat-level-saying-another-attackmay-be-imminent/2017/05/24/dd5367e8-3fec-11e7-b29f-f40ffced2ddb_story.html|title=Manchester bombing probe expands with arrests on two continents|first1=Griff|last1=Witte|first2=Karla|last2=Adam|first3=Sudarsan|last3=Raghavan|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524074250/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/british-prime-minister-raises-nations-threat-level-saying-another-attackmay-be-imminent/2017/05/24/dd5367e8-3fec-11e7-b29f-f40ffced2ddb_story.html|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> but not the date.<ref name=bbc6102>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40056102|title=Manchester attack: Police make tenth arrest|publisher=BBC News|date=26 May 2017|accessdate=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526071041/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40056102|archivedate=26 May 2017}}</ref> According to a Libyan official, the brothers spoke on the phone about 15 minutes before the attack was carried out.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/26/europe/manchester-terror-attack-uk/index.html|title=Manchester bomber spoke to brother before attack|last=Smith-Spark|first=Laura|last2=Gorani|first2=Hala|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|access-date=26 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526122050/http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/26/europe/manchester-terror-attack-uk/index.html|archivedate=26 May 2017}}</ref> On 1 November 2017, the UK requested Libya to extradite the bomber's younger brother, Hashem Abedi to return to the UK to face trial for complicity in the murder of the 22 people killed in the explosion.<ref name=\"GdnExdradit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/nov/01/uk-requests-extradition-of-hashem-abedi-over-manchester-arena-attack|title=UK requests extradition of Hashem Abedi over Manchester Arena attack|last=Pidd|first=Helen|date=1 November 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=1 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102014449/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/nov/01/uk-requests-extradition-of-hashem-abedi-over-manchester-arena-attack|archivedate=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nPhotographs of the remains of the [[Improvised explosive device|IED]] published by ''[[The New York Times]]'' indicated that it had comprised an explosive charge inside a lightweight metal container which was carried within a black vest or a blue [[Karrimor]] backpack. Most of the fatalities occurred in a ring around the bomber. His torso was propelled by the blast through the doors to the arena, possibly indicating that the explosive charge was held in the backpack and blew him forward on detonation. A small device thought to have possibly been a hand-held detonator was also found.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-arena-bomb-materials-photos.html|title=Found at the Scene in Manchester: Shrapnel, a Backpack and a Battery|last=Chivers|first=C.L.|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524174025/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-arena-bomb-materials-photos.html|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> US Congressman [[Michael McCaul]], chairman of the [[House Homeland Security Committee]], indicated that the bomb contained the explosive [[acetone peroxide|TATP]], which has been used in previous bombings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/manchester-attack-latest-u-s-lawmaker-says-u-k-bomb-showed-sophistication-1.3426624|title=Manchester attack latest: U.S. lawmaker says U.K. bomb showed 'sophistication'|date=24 May 2017|work=CTVNews|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626030225/http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/manchester-attack-latest-u-s-lawmaker-says-u-k-bomb-showed-sophistication-1.3426624|archivedate=26 June 2017}}</ref> According to Manchester police, the explosive device used by Abedi was the design of a skilled bomb-maker and had a back-up means of detonation.<ref>{{cite news|title=The hunt is on for the Manchester bomber's accomplices|url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21722697-it-seems-salman-abedi-did-not-act-aloneand-his-fellow-plotters-could-strike-again-hunt|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525231928/http://www.economist.com/news/britain/21722697-it-seems-salman-abedi-did-not-act-aloneand-his-fellow-plotters-could-strike-again-hunt|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> Police also said Salman Abedi \"bought most of Manchester bomb components himself\" and that he was alone during much of the time before carrying out the Manchester bombing.<ref name=\"GdnExdradit\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/30/salman-abedi-bought-most-of-manchester-bomb-components-himself-6673508/|title=Salman Abedi 'bought most of Manchester bomb components himself'|first=Jen|last=Mills|work=[[Metro News]]|date=30 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828070730/http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/30/salman-abedi-bought-most-of-manchester-bomb-components-himself-6673508/|archivedate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 May, police released images showing Abedi on the night of the bombing, taken from [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]] footage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40072786 |title=Manchester attack: CCTV shows bomber before arena blast |publisher=BBC News |date=28 May 2017 |accessdate=29 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528235059/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40072786 |archivedate=28 May 2017  }}</ref> Further images showed Abedi walking around Manchester with a blue suitcase.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/29/europe/mi5-internal-inquiry-abedi/index.html|title=Did you see Manchester bomber with blue suitcase?|last=Roberts|first=Elizabeth|last2=Gast|first2=Phil|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|access-date=31 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530211251/http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/29/europe/mi5-internal-inquiry-abedi/index.html|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US intelligence sources, Abedi was identified by the [[bank card]] that he had with him and the identification confirmed using [[Facial recognition system|facial recognition technology]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/manchester-concert-explosion/manchester-bombing-british-police-release-new-photos-suspect-salman-abedi-n765476|title=British police release new photos of arena bombing suspect|publisher=[[NBC News]]|access-date=27 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527214413/http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/manchester-concert-explosion/manchester-bombing-british-police-release-new-photos-suspect-salman-abedi-n765476|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nA total of 22 people were arrested in connection with the attack, but had all been released without charge by 11 June following the police's conclusion that Abedi was likely to have acted alone, even though others may have been aware of his plans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/those-arrested-manchester-arena-attack-13170282|title=All those arrested since Manchester Arena attack released without charge|last=Cox|first=Charlotte|date=11 June 2017|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|access-date=17 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611162404/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/those-arrested-manchester-arena-attack-13170282|archivedate=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 July 2019, Salman Abedi's brother Hashem was charged with murder, attempted murder and conspiracy to cause an explosion. He had been arrested in Libya and [[Extradition|extradited]] to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jul/17/hashem-abedi-brother-of-manchester-arena-bomber-being-extradited-to-uk|title=Manchester Arena bomber's brother held in UK after extradition|work=The Guardian|date=17 July 2019|accessdate=18 July 2019}}</ref> His trial began on 5 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-51371530|title=Hashem Abedi: Manchester Arena attack brother 'equally guilty'|date=4 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> On 17 March, Hashem Abedi was found guilty on 22 charges of murder, on the grounds that he had helped his brother to source the materials used in the bombing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-51926162 |title=Manchester Arena bombing: Hashem Abedi guilty of 22 murders |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===News leaks===\nWithin hours of the attack, Abedi's name and other information given confidentially to security services in the United States and France were [[News leak|leaked to the news media]], leading to condemnation from [[Home Secretary]] [[Amber Rudd]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2017-40026413|title=Manchester attack: US leaks about bomber irritating \u2013 Rudd|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524114710/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2017-40026413|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=leaks>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/us-officials-leak-more-manchester-details-hours-after-uk-rebuke |title=US officials leak more Manchester details hours after UK rebuke |newspaper=The Guardian |date=24 May 2017 |first1=Ewen |last1=MacAskill |first2=Julian |last2=Borger |location=London & Washington |accessdate=24 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524153934/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/us-officials-leak-more-manchester-details-hours-after-uk-rebuke |archivedate=24 May 2017  }}</ref> Following the publication of crime scene photographs of the backpack bomb used in the attack in the 24 May edition of ''The New York Times'', UK counterterrorism police chiefs said the release of the material was detrimental to the investigation.<ref name=\"BBC 24 May 2017\">{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40038630|title= Manchester attack: 'Fury' at US 'evidence' photos leak|date= 24 May 2017|publisher= BBC News|accessdate= 24 May 2017|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170524213432/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40038630|archivedate= 24 May 2017|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May, [[Greater Manchester Police]] said it had stopped sharing information on the attack with the US intelligence services. May said she would make clear to [[President Trump]] that \"intelligence that has been shared must be made secure.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40040210|title=Manchester attack: Police 'not sharing information with US'|date=25 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525075547/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40040210|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> Trump described the leaks to the news media as \"deeply troubling\", and pledged to carry out a full investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40048565|title=Manchester attack: Trump condemns media leaks|date=25 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525142202/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40048565|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> British officials blamed the leaks on \"the breakdown of normal discipline at the White House and in the US security services\".<ref name=\"GdnWHRift\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/25/white-house-rift-with-security-agencies-aided-manchester-bomb-leaks|title=White House rift with security agencies 'aided Manchester bomb leaks'|first1=Ewen|last1=MacAskill|first2=Julian|last2=Borger|location=London & Washington|date=25 May 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525194616/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/25/white-house-rift-with-security-agencies-aided-manchester-bomb-leaks|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> ''New York Times'' editor [[Dean Baquet]] declined to apologise for publishing the backpack bomb photographs, saying \"We live in different press worlds\" and that the material was not classified at the highest level.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40067421/manchester-attack-editor-defends-publishing-leaked-photos|title=Manchester attack: Editor defends publishing leaked photos|date=27 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|access-date=27 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527011659/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40067421/manchester-attack-editor-defends-publishing-leaked-photos|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May, US Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson]] said the United States government accepted responsibility for the leaks.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. takes 'full responsibility' for Manchester intelligence leaks \u2013 Tillerson|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-security-manchester-tillerson-idUKKBN18M1E4|accessdate=30 May 2017|agency=Reuters|date=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527095429/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-security-manchester-tillerson-idUKKBN18M1E4|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Links with the Muslim Brotherhood ===\nAccording to a secret recording unveiled by the BBC, Mostafa Graf, the imam of the [[Didsbury Mosque]] where Salman Abedi and his family were regulars, made a call for armed jihad 10 days before Abedi bought his concert ticket.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44729727|title=Mosque sermon 'called for armed jihad'|last=Titheradge|first=Ed Thomas and Noel|date=16 August 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=1 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nFollowing these revelations, the Manchester Police opened an investigation into the mosque and its Imam, who also fought with a Libyan Islamist militia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/aug/16/police-investigate-links-between-arena-bomber-and-manchester-imam|title=Manchester police investigate arena bomber's links to imam|last=Pidd|first=Helen|date=16 August 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref> Mostafa Graf is a member of the International Union of Muslim Scholars, an organisation founded by the Muslim Brotherhood and Yusuf al-Qaradawi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/gulf-qatar/islamist-group-rejects-terrorism-charge-by-states-boycotting-qatar-idUSL8N1O12V8|title=Islamist group rejects terrorism charge by states boycotting Qatar|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=1 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Al-Qaradawi is known for having claimed, \"Suicide bombings are a duty\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/gdpr-consent/|title=- The Washington Post|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nHaras Rafiq, head of the [[Quilliam]] think tank, told ''The Guardian'' that the Muslim Brotherhood runs the Didsbury Mosque.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/28/salman-abedi-manchester-arena-bomber-radicalisation|title=How Manchester bomber Salman Abedi was radicalised by his links to Libya|last=Doward|first=Jamie|last2=Cobain|first2=Ian|date=28 May 2017|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018|last3=Stephen|first3=Chris|last4=Quinn|first4=Ben}}</ref>\n\nThe Didsbury Mosque is controlled by The Islamic Centre (Manchester), an English association headed by Dr. Haytham al-Khaffaf, who is also a director of the Human Relief Foundation, a Muslim Brotherhood organisation blacklisted for terrorism by Israel.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beta.charitycommission.gov.uk/charity-details/?regid=327235&subid=0|title=Charity Details|website=beta.charitycommission.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/a-shadowy-web-traced-back-to-bradford-bzxshhbrz9z|title=A shadowy web traced back to Bradford|last=Norfolk|first=Andrew|date=17 August 2015|work=The Times|access-date=1 October 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> Between 2015 and 2016, al-Khaffaf's Human Relief Foundation received over \u00a31.5 million from the Qatar Charity, which is also subject of US counterterrorism surveillance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/06195282/filing-history|title=HUMAN RELIEF FOUNDATION \u2013 Filing history (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|page=see page 24 in the Group of companies' accounts made up to 31 December 2016|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=12 May 2009|title=Qatar Commits Usd 40 Million for Un Operations in Gaza|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09DOHA314_a.html|journal=WikiLeaks|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n{{Main|Reactions to the Manchester Arena bombing}}\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[File:St Ann's Square floral tribute panorama (02).jpg|thumb|Floral tributes to the victims of the attack in [[St Ann's Square, Manchester|St Ann's Square]] in Manchester city centre<!-- No period&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;see MOS:CAPFRAG -->]]\n<!-- PLEASE ADD ANY FURTHER CONDOLENCES TO THE DAUGHTER ARTICLE, WHERE THEY BELONG -->\nMay condemned the bombing,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/theresa-may-leads-condemnation-of-cowardly-manchester-attack|title=Theresa May leads condemnation of 'cowardly' Manchester attack|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=23 May 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|last2=Elgot|first2=Jessica|issn=0261-3077|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531063101/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/theresa-may-leads-condemnation-of-cowardly-manchester-attack|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref> and in a later statement following the [[June 2017 London Bridge attack|June 2017 London attack]], she stated that these attacks along with the [[2017 Westminster attack]] were \"bound together by the single evil ideology of Islamist extremism\" and said this extremism was \"a perversion of Islam\".<ref name=\"MayJune04\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/britain-security-may-statement-idUSL8N1J10GH|title=TEXT-UK Prime Minister May's statement following London attack|date=4 June 2017|agency=Reuters|access-date=5 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604150824/http://www.reuters.com/article/britain-security-may-statement-idUSL8N1J10GH|archivedate=4 June 2017}}</ref> [[Queen Elizabeth II]] expressed her sympathy to the families of the victims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.royal.uk/message-her-majesty-queen-lord-lieutenant-greater-manchester|title=A message from Her Majesty The Queen to the Lord-Lieutenant of Greater Manchester|last=Jenny.minard|date=23 May 2017|work=The Royal Family|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523132220/https://www.royal.uk/message-her-majesty-queen-lord-lieutenant-greater-manchester|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> Campaigning for [[2017 United Kingdom general election|the general election]] was suspended by all political parties for two days after the attack.<ref name=\"ITV News GE2017\">{{cite news | title=Campaigning suspended as world leaders pay respects | website=ITV News | date=23 May 2017 | url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-23/campaigning-suspended-as-world-leaders-pay-respects/ | accessdate=23 May 2017 | quote=Leaders of political parties did not hesitate to suspend General Election campaigning in the wake of the terror attack in Manchester. ... Campaigning for the 8 June vote will remain suspended for a second day on Wednesday. | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523231153/http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-23/campaigning-suspended-as-world-leaders-pay-respects/ | archivedate=23 May 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"GECampaign\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/23/general-election-campaigning-suspended-after-manchester-attack|title=General election campaigning suspended after Manchester attack|date=22 May 2017|work=The Guardian|location=London|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523040412/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/23/general-election-campaigning-suspended-after-manchester-attack|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> The [[Mayor of Greater Manchester]], [[Andy Burnham]], called the attack \"evil\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-attack-mayor-andy-burnham-says-spirit-of-manchester-will-prevail-after-evil-act-a3545916.html|title=Andy Burnham says spirit of Manchester will prevail after 'evil act'|date=23 May 2017|work=London Evening Standard|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523095334/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-attack-mayor-andy-burnham-says-spirit-of-manchester-will-prevail-after-evil-act-a3545916.html|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> and announced a vigil in [[Albert Square, Manchester|Albert Square]] the following evening,<ref name=\"updates bbc\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-england-manchester-40007967|title=Manchester Arena explosion: Latest updates|date=23 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523070932/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-england-manchester-40007967|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> which thousands attended.<ref name=\"corbyn\">{{cite web|last1=Edwards|first1=Peter|title=Corbyn attends Manchester vigil and insists: \"Our hearts are broken but our resolve has never been stronger\"|url=https://labourlist.org/2017/05/corbyn-attends-manchester-vigil-and-insists-our-hears-are-broken-but-our-resolve-has-never-been-stronger/|website=Labour List|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708224003/https://labourlist.org/2017/05/corbyn-attends-manchester-vigil-and-insists-our-hears-are-broken-but-our-resolve-has-never-been-stronger/|archivedate=8 July 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/nick-ferrari/manchester-mayor-bomber-was-a-terrorist-not-muslim/ Manchester Mayor: Bomber Was A Terrorist, Not A Muslim] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605062343/http://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/nick-ferrari/manchester-mayor-bomber-was-a-terrorist-not-muslim/ |date=5 June 2017 }}, lbc.co.uk, 24 May 2017</ref> The [[Muslim Council of Britain]] also condemned the attack.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-arena-bombing-everything-we-know-suicide-attack-killed-injured-ariana-grande-concert-isis-a7751031.html | title=Manchester Arena bombing: Everything we know about the suicide attack that killed at least 22 people | work=The Independent | date=23 May 2017 | accessdate=23 May 2017 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523131020/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-arena-bombing-everything-we-know-suicide-attack-killed-injured-ariana-grande-concert-isis-a7751031.html | archivedate=23 May 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May 2017, a national [[minute's silence]] was observed to remember the victims.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40041473 |title=Manchester attack: National minute's silence held |publisher=BBC News |date=25 May 2017 |accessdate=26 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526084023/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40041473 |archivedate=26 May 2017  }}</ref>\n\nPolice reported a 500% increase in anti-Muslim hate crimes in the Greater Manchester area in the month following the attack.<ref name=\"Gdn22617\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/22/islamophobic-attacks-manchester-increase-arena-attack|title=Islamophobic attacks in Manchester surge by 500% after arena attack|last=Halliday|first=Josh|date=22 June 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707155802/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/22/islamophobic-attacks-manchester-increase-arena-attack|archivedate=7 July 2017}}</ref> The [[Commission for Countering Extremism]] was created in the aftermath of the bombing.<ref name=\"PeckExtremism\">{{cite news|last1=Peck|first1=Tom|title=Theresa May to set up commission for countering extremism|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/theresa-may-conservative-manchester-attack-general-election-2017-commission-countering-extremism-a7759486.html|accessdate=18 March 2018|publisher=The Independent|date=27 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===International===\n{{tweet\n|text =           broken. from the bottom of my heart, i am so so sorry. i don't have words.\n|name =           Ariana Grande\n|username =       ArianaGrande \n|date =           23 May 2017 \n|ID =             866849021519966208 \n|reference =      <ref name=\"Ariana tweet\">{{cite tweet |author-link=Ariana Grande |user=ArianaGrande |number=866849021519966208 |date=23 May 2017 |title=broken. from the bottom of my heart, i am so so sorry. i don't have words. |link=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/866849021519966208 |access-date=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n<!-- PLEASE DON'T ADD QUOTES OF CONDOLENCE HERE!!!!! -->\nCondolences were expressed by the leaders and governments of dozens of countries,<ref name=\"Palazzo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/manchester-arena-shock-disbelief-police-confirm-19-killed-terrorist/|title='An attack on innocents': World reacts with shock and horror to Manchester explosion|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=23 May 2017|last=Palazzo|first=Chiara|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523041942/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/manchester-arena-shock-disbelief-police-confirm-19-killed-terrorist/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> United Nations [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary-General]] [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=56819|title=UN chief strongly condemns terrorist attack on Manchester concert|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523172429/http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=56819|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> [[Commonwealth Secretary-General]] [[Patricia Scotland]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thecommonwealth.org/media/news/statement-commonwealth-secretary-general-patricia-scotland-terror-attack-manchester|title=Statement by Commonwealth Secretary-General Patricia Scotland on terror attack in Manchester|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012082317/http://thecommonwealth.org/media/news/statement-commonwealth-secretary-general-patricia-scotland-terror-attack-manchester|archivedate=12 October 2017}}</ref> [[President of the European Commission]] [[Jean-Claude Juncker]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_STATEMENT-17-1434_en.htm|title=Statement by European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker following the attack in Manchester|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523072734/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_STATEMENT-17-1434_en.htm|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> [[Pope Francis]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/pope-francis-offers-condolences-for-manchester-attack-victims/|title=Pope Francis offers condolences to Manchester attack victims|work=Catholic Herald|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524092012/http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/pope-francis-offers-condolences-for-manchester-attack-victims/|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> and secretary general of the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] [[Yousef Al-Othaimeen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oic-oci.org/topic/?t_id=13607&t_ref=5926&lan=en|title=OIC Secretary General Condemns the Deadly Attack in Manchester, the United Kingdom|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAriana Grande posted on Twitter: \"broken. from the bottom of my heart, i am so so sorry. i don't have words. [''sic'']\"<ref name=\"Ariana tweet\" /> The tweet briefly became the most-liked tweet in history.<ref>Bloom, Ester. [https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/15/obamas-charlottesville-response-could-be-the-most-popular-tweet-ever.html \"Obama's response to Charlottesville is now the most 'liked' tweet of all time\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816111414/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/15/obamas-charlottesville-response-could-be-the-most-popular-tweet-ever.html |date=16 August 2017 }}, CNBC, 15 August 2017</ref> Grande suspended her tour and flew back to her mother's home in Florida.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ariana-grande-suspends-tour-after-manchester-attack-w483880|title=Ariana Grande Suspends Tour After Manchester Attack|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523212900/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ariana-grande-suspends-tour-after-manchester-attack-w483880|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ariana-grande-returns-home-to-florida-after-manchester-attack-w483730|title=Ariana Grande Returns Home to Florida After Manchester Concert Attack|work=US Weekly|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524170722/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ariana-grande-returns-home-to-florida-after-manchester-attack-w483730|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2017, a performance to benefit the Manchester bombing victims was held in New York City's [[The Cutting Room]], called \"Break Free: United for Manchester\", with Broadway theatre and television performers interpreting Ariana Grande songs.<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/BREAK-FREE-Broadway-Performers-to-Throw-Benefit-Concert-for-Manchester-Victims-20170629 \"Break Free: Broadway Performers to Throw Manchester Benefit Concert\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809170833/http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/BREAK-FREE-Broadway-Performers-to-Throw-Benefit-Concert-for-Manchester-Victims-20170629 |date=9 August 2017 }}, BroadwayWorld.com, 29 June 2017</ref>\n\n===One Love Manchester===\n{{Main|One Love Manchester}}\nOn 4 June, Ariana Grande hosted a [[benefit concert]] in Manchester, entitled \"One Love Manchester\" at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground]] that was broadcast live on television, radio and social media. At the concert, Grande performed along with several other high-profile artists. Free tickets were offered to those who had attended the show on 22 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40086336|title=Manchester attack: Ariana Grande to play benefit concert on Sunday|publisher=BBC News|date=30 May 2017|access-date=30 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530153707/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40086336|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> The benefit concert and associated Red Cross fund raised \u00a310&nbsp;million for victims of the attack by early June<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-40153433|title=One Love Manchester: Joy shines through pain at benefit concert|last=Youngs| first=Ian|date=5 June 2017|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607021042/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-40153433|archivedate=7 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4805251/ariana-grande-manchester-benefit-concert-fundraising| title=Ariana Grande's Manchester Benefit Concert Raised $13 Million|last=TIME|website=Time| access-date=6 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605221041/http://time.com/4805251/ariana-grande-manchester-benefit-concert-fundraising|archivedate=5 June 2017}}</ref> and \u00a317&nbsp;million by August.<ref>Blistein, Jon. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/families-of-ariana-grande-concert-attack-victims-to-receive-324000-w498012 \"Families of Ariana Grande Concert Attack Victims to Receive $324,000\"], ''Rolling Stone'', 15 August 2017</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''{{'}}s Vulture section ranked the event as the No. 1 concert of 2017.<ref name=Vulture2017>Lockett, Dee. [http://www.vulture.com/2017/12/the-10-best-concerts-of-2017.html \"The 10 Best Concerts of 2017\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222044700/http://www.vulture.com/2017/12/the-10-best-concerts-of-2017.html |date=22 December 2017 }}, ''[[New York Magazine]]'', 21 December 2017</ref>\n\n==The Kerslake Report==\nOn 27 March 2018, the Kerslake Report, \"an independent review into the preparedness for, and emergency response to, the Manchester Arena attack on 22nd May 2017\",<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\">{{cite web | title= The Kerslake Report: An independent review into the preparedness for, and emergency response to, the Manchester Arena attack on 22nd May 2017 |url= https://www.kerslakearenareview.co.uk/media/1022/kerslake_arena_review_printed_final.pdf | author1= Bob Kerslake|author2= Independent panel members |date= 27 March 2018| website= www.kerslakearenareview.co.uk| publisher= | accessdate= 27 March 2018|author1-link= Bob Kerslake }}</ref> was published; it found that the [[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]] was \"brought to a point of paralysis\".<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|5.155}}\n\nThe Kerslake Report \"largely praised\" the [[Greater Manchester Police]] and [[British Transport Police]], and noted that it was \"fortuitous\" that the [[North West Ambulance Service]] was unaware of the declaration of Operation Plato, a protocol under which all responders should have been withdrawn from the arena foyer.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|5.40}}\n\nIt was critical of [[Vodafone]], for the \"catastrophic failure\"<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|5.47}} of an emergency helpline hosted on a platform provided by [[Content Guru]], saying that delays in getting information caused \"significant stress and upset\" to families.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|17}} It also expressed criticism of some news media, saying, \"To have experienced such intrusive and overbearing behaviour at a time of such enormous vulnerability seemed to us to be completely and utterly unacceptable\",<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|19}} but noting that, \"We recognise that this was some, but by no means all of the media and that the media also have a positive and important role to play.\"<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|19}}\n\n==Popular Culture==\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of terrorist incidents in Great Britain]]\n* [[List of terrorist incidents in May 2017]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Greater Manchester|United Kingdom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|May 2017 Manchester attack}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40012738 Manchester attack: Who were the victims?] (BBC News)\n*[http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/salman-abedi-manchester-arena-bomber-13601393 The making of a monster: How Manchester boy Salman Abedi became a mass murderer] ''Manchester Evening News'', 19 September 2017\n*[https://www.kerslakearenareview.co.uk/media/1022/kerslake_arena_review_printed_final.pdf The Kerslake Report], March 2018\n\n<!-- Consensus is against adding [[Template:Ariana Grande]]. See talk page consensus headbar. -->\n{{Islamic terrorism in Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manchester Arena bombing}}\n[[Category:2010s in Manchester]]\n[[Category:2017 in England]]\n[[Category:2017 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ariana Grande]]\n[[Category:Attacks on music venues]]\n[[Category:Improvised explosive device bombings in England]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorism in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorist incidents in 2017]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2017]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in England]]\n[[Category:May 2017 crimes in Europe]]\n[[Category:May 2017 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Murder in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Stadium disasters]]\n[[Category:Suicide bombings in 2017]]\n[[Category:Suicide bombings in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in the United Kingdom in 2017]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 suicide bombing}}\n{{about|the 2017 suicide bombing|the IRA bombing in 1996|1996 Manchester bombing|other bombings|Manchester bombing (disambiguation){{!}}Manchester bombing}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| map              = {{Location map many | Greater Manchester#United Kingdom\n| width        = 280\n| float        = centre\n| label        = Manchester Arena\n| position     = right\n| background   = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|53|29|17.3|N|2|14|34|W}}\n}}\n| partof           = [[Islamic terrorism in Europe]]\n| image            = Manchester Arena exterior, (3) May19.jpg\n| image_size       = 300px\n| alt              = \n| caption          = [[Manchester Arena]] in 2019\n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = File:Manchester bombing.png\n| map_caption      = \n| title            = \n| location         = [[Manchester Arena]],<br />[[Manchester]], England\n| target           = Concert-goers\n| coordinates      = {{coord|53|29|17.3|N|2|14|34|W|display=inline,title}}\n| date             = {{start date and age|2017|05|22|df=yes}}\n| time             = 22:31<!--NOT 22:33. That's when the first emergency calls were made.-->\n| timezone         = [[British Summer Time|BST]]\n| weapon           = [[Acetone peroxide|TATP]] [[nail bomb]]\n| type             = [[Suicide bombing]]\n| fatalities       = 23 (including the perpetrator) <!--Consensus is to phrase this along the lines of \"23, including the attacker\", as opposed to \"22, excluding the attacker\".-->\n| injuries         = 800+<ref name=\"800Injured\"/><br />Hospitalised: 112<ref>{{cite web |title=Elite sports centre to treat bomb victims |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-43455692 |website=BBC News |date=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n| victims          = \n| perpetrators     = Salman & Hashem Abedi<ref>{{Cite news|title=Manchester Arena bombing: Hashem Abedi guilty of 22 murders|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-51926162|publisher=BBC News|date=17 Mar 2020|access-date=17 Mar 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| motive           = [[Islamic extremism]]<ref name=\"MayJune04\"/>\n| numparts         = \n| dfens            = \n| inquiry          = \n| coroner          = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module           = \n}}\nOn 22 May 2017, an [[Islamic extremism|Islamic extremist]] [[suicide bombing attack|suicide bomber]] detonated a [[nail bomb|shrapnel-laden]] [[homemade bomb]] as people were leaving the [[Manchester Arena]], England following [[Dangerous Woman Tour|a concert]] by the American singer [[Ariana Grande]].\n\nTwenty-three<!-- Consensus is to phrase this along the lines of \"23, including the attacker\", as opposed to \"22, excluding the attacker\" --> people died, including the attacker, and 139 were wounded, more than half of them children. Several hundred more suffered [[psychological trauma]]. The bomber was Salman Ramadan Abedi, a 22-year-old local man of Libyan ancestry. After initial suspicions of a terrorist network, police later said they believed Abedi had largely acted alone but that others had been aware of his plans. In March 2020, the bomber's brother, Hashem Abedi, was found guilty of 22 counts of murder in relation to the attack.\n\nThe incident was the deadliest terrorist attack and the first suicide bombing in the United Kingdom since the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]].\n\n==Attack==\nOn 22 May 2017 at 22:31<!-- NOT 22:33. That's when the first emergency calls were made. --> [[British Summer Time|BST]] ([[UTC+01:00]]),<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|3.8}} a [[Suicide bombing|suicide bomber]] detonated an improvised explosive device, [[Nail bomb|packed with nuts and bolts to act as shrapnel]], in the [[foyer]] area of the [[Manchester Arena]]. The attack took place after an Ariana Grande concert that was part of her 2017 [[Dangerous Woman Tour]].<ref name=\"BBCconfirm2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40007886|title=Manchester Arena blast: 19 dead and more than 50 hurt|date=22 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|access-date=22 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522223115/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40007886|archivedate=22 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/ariana-grande-concert-manchester-arena-explosion/|title=UK police: 22 confirmed dead after terror incident at Ariana Grande concert|publisher=[[CBSN|CBS News]]|date=22 May 2017|access-date=22 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523062040/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/ariana-grande-concert-manchester-arena-explosion/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> 14,200 people attended the concert.<ref>{{cite news|title=Manchester One Love concert: 'Thousands make false ticket claims'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40118865|publisher=BBC News|date=1 June 2017|access-date=1 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601150506/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40118865|archivedate=1 June 2017}}</ref> Many exiting concert-goers and waiting parents were in the foyer at the time of the explosion. According to evidence presented at the [[Coroner (England and Wales)|coroner's inquest]], the bomb was strong enough to kill people up to {{convert|20|m|ft}} away.<ref name=\"inquest\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/09/manchester-arena-bomb-designed-kill-largest-number-innocents|title=Manchester Arena bomb was designed to kill largest number of innocents|last=Pidd|first=Helen|date=9 June 2017|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=10 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610042404/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/09/manchester-arena-bomb-designed-kill-largest-number-innocents|archivedate=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Greater Manchester Police]] declared the incident a terrorist attack and [[suicide bombing]]. It was the deadliest attack in the United Kingdom since the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]].<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|3}}\n\n===Aftermath===\nAbout three hours after the bombing, police conducted a [[controlled explosion]] on a suspicious item of clothing in [[Cathedral Gardens]]. This was later confirmed to have been abandoned clothing and not dangerous.<ref name=\"BBC-attack-23-05-2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40010124|title=Manchester Arena attack: 22 dead and 59 hurt|publisher=BBC News|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523061202/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40010124|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/23/isis-claim-responsibility-for-the-manchester-attack-that-killed-22-6655764/|title=Isis claim responsibility for the Manchester attack that killed 22.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523131922/http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/23/isis-claim-responsibility-for-the-manchester-attack-that-killed-22-6655764/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nResidents and taxi companies in Manchester offered free transport or accommodation via Twitter to those left stranded at the concert.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|4.85}} Parents were separated from their children attending the concert in the aftermath of the explosion. A nearby hotel served as a shelter for people displaced by the bombing, with officials directing separated parents and children there.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|4.85}} Manchester's [[Sikhism|Sikh]] temples ([[gurdwara]]s) along with local homeowners, hotels and venues offered shelter to survivors of the attack.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pells|first1=Rachael|title=Manchester Sikh temples offer food and shelter to people affected by terror attack|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-sikh-temples-food-shelter-people-terror-attack-suicide-bomb-harinder-kukreja-gurdwara-a7750881.html|accessdate=25 May 2017|work=[[The Independent]]|date=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523131036/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-sikh-temples-food-shelter-people-terror-attack-suicide-bomb-harinder-kukreja-gurdwara-a7750881.html|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Operation Temperer May 2017 (1).jpg|thumb|British military personnel alongside armed police as part of [[Operation Temperer]] in response to the raised threat level<!-- No full stop. See MOS:CAPFRAG -->]]\n[[Manchester Victoria station|Manchester Victoria railway station]], which is partly underneath the arena, was evacuated and closed, and services were cancelled.<ref name=\"BBCconfirm2\"/><ref name=\"abc\">{{Cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/police-respond-reports-incident-manchester-arena/story?id=47569092|title=Deaths, injuries after reports of explosion at Ariana Grande concert at Manchester Arena: Police|date=22 May 2017|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=22 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523013947/http://abcnews.go.com/International/police-respond-reports-incident-manchester-arena/story?id=47569092|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> The explosion caused structural damage to the station, which remained closed until the damage had been assessed and repaired, resulting in disruption to train and tram services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Structural damage to Victoria Station after bomb|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-26/structural-damage-to-victoria-station-after-bomb/|publisher=[[itv.com|ITV]] News|accessdate=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527131405/http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-26/structural-damage-to-victoria-station-after-bomb/|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref> The station reopened to traffic eight days later, following the completion of police investigation work and repairs to the fabric of the building.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|4.57}}\n\nAfter a [[Civil Contingencies Committee|COBRA]] meeting with [[Greater Manchester Police|Greater Manchester's Chief Constable]], [[Ian Hopkins]], on 23 May, Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] announced that the UK's [[UK Threat Levels|terror threat level]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mi5.gov.uk/threat-levels |title=Threat Levels |website=Security \\service \u2013 [[MI5]] |accessdate=26 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525220445/https://www.mi5.gov.uk/threat-levels |archivedate=25 May 2017  }} Threat levels in Great Britain and in Northern Ireland from international and Northern Ireland-related terrorism, published here, are deemed \"critical\" for a period following the attack.</ref> was raised to \"critical\", its highest level.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|5.247}} The threat level remained critical until 27 May, when it was reduced to its previous level of severe.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40069959 |title=Manchester attack: Terror threat reduced from critical to severe |publisher=BBC News |date=27 May 2017 |accessdate=27 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527101510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40069959 |archivedate=27 May 2017  }}</ref> In the aftermath of the attack [[Operation Temperer]] was activated for the first time, allowing up to 5,000 soldiers to reinforce armed police in protecting parts of the country.<ref name=\"ITV News threat level 2017\">{{cite news |title=PM Theresa May raises UK threat level to 'critical' |website=ITV News |date=23 May 2017 |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-05-23/uk-threat-level-raised-to-critical-severe/ |access-date=23 May 2017 |quote=Raising the level to critical means that military personnel could be deployed to support armed police officers \u2013 part of a plan known as Operation Temperer. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523215312/http://www.itv.com/news/2017-05-23/uk-threat-level-raised-to-critical-severe/ |archivedate=23 May 2017  }}</ref><ref name=\"alan travis temperer twitter\">{{cite tweet |first=Alan |last=Travis |retweet=The Guardian |user=alantravis40 |number=867119049028890624 |date=23 May 2017 |title=PM says Critical Threat level's Operation Temperer will use up to 5,000 troops to take over armed police patrol duties under police command.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40068803/manchester-attack-pm-says-terror-threat-level-reduced-from-critical|access-date=27 May 2017|title=Manchester attack: PM says terror threat level reduced from critical|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530171831/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40068803/manchester-attack-pm-says-terror-threat-level-reduced-from-critical|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> Tours of the [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]] and the [[Changing the Queen's Life Guard|Changing of the Guard]] ceremony at [[Buckingham Palace]] were cancelled on 24 May, and troops were deployed to guard government buildings in London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi.html|title=3 Men Arrested in Investigation of Manchester Bombing|last=Bennhold|first=Katrin|date=24 May 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=24 May 2017|last2=Castle|first2=Stephen|issn=0362-4331|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524151028/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi.html|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 May, the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]], via the Nashir [[Telegram (messaging service)|Telegram]] channel, claimed the attack was carried out by \"a soldier of the [[Khilafah]]\". The message called the attack \"an endeavor to terrorize the [[mushrik]]in, and in response to their transgressions against the lands of the Muslims.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/23/world/europe/manchester-arena-attack-ariana-grande.html| title=ISIS Claims Responsibility for Manchester Concert Attack; Toll Rises to 22|date=23 May 2017|work=The New York Times|last2=Erlanger|first2=Steven|last1=Yeginsu|first1=Ceylan|accessdate=23 May 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523083054/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/23/world/europe/manchester-arena-attack-ariana-grande.html| archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://time.com/4790201/isis-manchester-concert-terrorist-attack/|title=ISIS Claims Responsibility For Manchester Concert Terrorist Attack|date=23 May 2017|work=Time|last1=Samuelson|first1=Kate|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523125036/http://time.com/4790201/isis-manchester-concert-terrorist-attack/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-arena-attack-isis-responsible-claim-suicide-bombing-islamic-state-ariana-grande-concert-a7751221.html|title=Isis has claimed responsibility for the Manchester Arena attack|date=23 May 2017|work=The Independent|last1=Dearden|first1=Lizzie|accessdate=23 May 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523121220/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-arena-attack-isis-responsible-claim-suicide-bombing-islamic-state-ariana-grande-concert-a7751221.html| archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi's sister said that he was motivated by revenge for Muslim children killed by [[American-led intervention in Syria|American airstrikes in Syria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/25/salman-abedi-wanted-revenge-us-air-strikes-syriamanchester-bombers| title=Salman Abedi 'wanted revenge' for US air strikes in Syria,&nbsp;Manchester bomber's sister says|work=The Telegraph|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525050239/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/25/salman-abedi-wanted-revenge-us-air-strikes-syriamanchester-bombers/|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/manchester-bomber-fought-in-libya-1495662073|title=Manchester Bomber Believed Muslims Were Mistreated, Sought Revenge|last=Morajea|first=Hassan|date=25 May 2017|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|last2=Kantchev|first2=Georgi|issn=0099-9660|last3=Bird| first3=Mike|last4=Gold|first4=Riva|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524214833/https://www.wsj.com/articles/manchester-bomber-fought-in-libya-1495662073|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Arena remained closed until September 2017, with scheduled concerts either cancelled or moved to other venues.<ref name=\"concerts\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40275744| title=Manchester Arena to stay closed until September|publisher=BBC News|date=14 June 2017|accessdate=14 June 2017| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614122402/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40275744|archivedate=14 June 2017}}</ref> It reopened on 9 September, with a benefit concert featuring [[Noel Gallagher]] and other acts associated with [[North West England]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40943849 |title=Manchester Arena: Noel Gallagher to headline reopening concert |publisher=BBC News |date=16 August 2017 |accessdate=16 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816071206/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40943849 |archivedate=16 August 2017  }}</ref>\n\nMay announced an extra \u00a313 million reimbursement from central government to Manchester's public services for most of the costs incurred by the attack in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-42808483 |title=Manchester Arena attack: Theresa May announces payout package |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=24 January 2018 |accessdate=24 January 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124202311/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-42808483 |archivedate=24 January 2018  }}</ref> Later that month, Chris Parker, a homeless man who stole from victims of the attack, was jailed for 4 years and three months.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-42876790| title=Manchester Arena attack 'hero' jailed for theft|work=BBC News|date=30 January 2018|accessdate=30 January 2018|url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130135828/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-42876790|archivedate=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\n<!-- NO LIST OF VICTIMS PLEASE PER TALK PAGE CONSENSUS: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:2017_Manchester_Arena_bombing/Archive_2#RfC:_Should_the_victims_be_named.3F --><!--NOTE: there were TWENTYTHREE dead, 22 victims and the bomber. It's not correct to speak of 22 dead people. 22 concert-goers, or victims; 23 people.-->\nThe blast killed the attacker and 22<!-- Consensus is to phrase this along the lines of \"23, including the attacker\", as opposed to \"22, excluding the attacker\". --> concert-goers and parents who were in the entrance waiting to pick up their children following the show; 119 people were initially reported as injured.<ref name=\"Metro.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/23/12-children-under-16-are-among-manchester-terror-attack-injured-6655858/|title=Twelve children under 16 are among Manchester terror attack injured|last=Metro.co.uk|first=Nicole Morley for|date=23 May 2017|website=Metro|url-status=live|access-date=29 May 2017|quote=22 people have been killed and 59 were taken to hospital following the blast. 119 people were injured in total.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523154239/http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/23/12-children-under-16-are-among-manchester-terror-attack-injured-6655858/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GdnSing\" /> This number was revised by police to 250 on 22 June, with the addition of severe [[psychological trauma]] and minor injuries.<ref name=\"250Injured\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/number-people-injured-manchester-arena-13223904|title=Number of people injured in Manchester terror attack rises to 250|last=Abbit|first=Beth|date=22 June 2017|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|access-date=26 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622155426/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/number-people-injured-manchester-arena-13223904|archivedate=22 June 2017}}</ref> In May 2018, the number of injured was revised to 800.<ref name=\"800Injured\">{{cite web|title=Arena bomb 'injured more than 800'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-44129386|website=BBC News|accessdate=16 May 2018|date=16 May 2018}}</ref> The dead included ten people aged under 20; the youngest victim was an eight-year-old girl and the oldest was a 51-year-old woman.<ref name=\"GdnSing\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/go-sing-with-the-angels-families-and-friends-pay-tribute-to-manchester-victims|title=Go sing with the angels: families pay tribute to Manchester victims|last=Topping|first=Alexandra|date=24 May 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525171256/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/go-sing-with-the-angels-families-and-friends-pay-tribute-to-manchester-victims|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> Of the 22 victims, twenty were [[Briton]]s and two were British-based Polish nationals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-victims-named-dead-terror--13080028|first=Alex|last=Pesic|title=These are the 22 victims of the Manchester Arena terror attack|date=29 May 2017|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|accessdate=14 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616133649/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-victims-named-dead-terror--13080028|archivedate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[North West Ambulance Service]] reported that 60 of its ambulances attended the scene, carried 59 people to local hospitals, and treated [[walking wounded]] on site.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|2}} Of those hospitalised, 12 were children under the age of 16.<ref name=\"Metro.uk\" />  In total, 112 people were hospitalized for their injuries, and 27 were treated for injuries that did not require hospitalization.  Out of this total of 139, 79 were children.<ref name=\"GdnExdradit\"/>\n\nThe first doctor thought to have been on scene was an off-duty consultant anaesthetist, Michael Daley.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gulland|first=Anne|date=30 June 2017|title=Doctors commended for their bravery in response to terrorist incidents|url=http://www.bmj.com/content/357/bmj.j3184|journal=BMJ|volume=357|pages=j3184|doi=10.1136/bmj.j3184|issn=0959-8138|pmid=28667098|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630171447/http://www.bmj.com/content/357/bmj.j3184|archivedate=30 June 2017}}</ref> In recognition of his bravery for the role he played in the immediate medical response to the incident, Daley's name was entered into the [[British Medical Association]] Book of Valour in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/about-us/who-we-are/awards-and-honours|title=BMA \u2013 Awards and honours|website=bma.org.uk|accessdate=3 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730023412/https://www.bma.org.uk/about-us/who-we-are/awards-and-honours|archivedate=30 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Attacker==\n<!--DO NOT ADD ANY INFOBOXES WITHOUT FIRST CONSULTING THE TALK PAGE -->\nThe bomber, Salman Ramadan Abedi, was a 22-year-old British Muslim of Libyan ancestry.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web |first1=Martin |last1=Evans |first2=Victoria |last2=Ward |first3=Robert |last3=Mendick |first4=Ben |last4=Farmer |first5=Hayley |last5=Dixon |first6=Danny |last6=Boyle |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/everything-know-salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber/ |title=Everything we know about Salman Abedi, the Manchester suicide bomber |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=26 May 2017 |accessdate=26 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525235330/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/everything-know-salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber/ |archivedate=25 May 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/manchester-bombing-attack-salman-abedi-teenage-aggression-family-614358|title=The Manchester bomber was a promising young man who went off the rails, says a religious leader who knew him|last=Paton|first=Callum|date=23 May 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524195149/http://www.newsweek.com/manchester-bombing-attack-salman-abedi-teenage-aggression-family-614358|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> He was born in Manchester on 31 December 1994 to a [[Salafism|Salafi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/story/the-manchester-bomber-grew-up-in-a-neighborhood-struggling-with-extremism|title=The Manchester bomber grew up in a neighborhood struggling with extremism|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice.com]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525190723/https://news.vice.com/story/the-manchester-bomber-grew-up-in-a-neighborhood-struggling-with-extremism|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> family of Libyan-born refugees who had settled in south Manchester after fleeing to the UK to escape the government of [[Muammar Gaddafi]]. He had two brothers and a sister.<ref name=\"who was salman abedi\">{{cite news|title=Manchester attack: Who was Salman Abedi?|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-40019135|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524072701/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-40019135|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber-know/|title=Salman Abedi named as the Manchester suicide bomber \u2013 what we know about him|last1=Evans|first1=Martin|last2=Ward|first2=Victoria|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=23 May 2017|quote=his parents were Libyan refugees who came to the UK to escape the Gaddafi regime|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523180222/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber-know/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> He grew up in the [[Whalley Range, Manchester|Whalley Range]] area and lived in [[Fallowfield]].<ref name=\"telegrsalman\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber-know/|title=Salman Abedi named as the Manchester suicide bomber \u2013 what we know about him|last1=Evans|first1=Martin|last2=Ward|first2=Victoria|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523180222/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber-know/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> Neighbours described the Abedi family as very traditional and \"super religious\".<ref>Connor, Richard (25 May 2017). [http://www.dw.com/en/manchester-bomber-a-life-on-the-move/a-38979272 Manchester bomber: A life on the move.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530111613/http://www.dw.com/en/manchester-bomber-a-life-on-the-move/a-38979272 |date=30 May 2017 }} Deutsche Welle. Retrieved 26 May 2017.</ref> Abedi, his elder brother,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/world/europe/92911194/the-face-of-hate-manchester-arena-attack-suspect-salman-abedis-home-raided  |title=The face of hate': Manchester Arena attack suspect Salman Abedi's home raided, disturbing book found |date =24 May 2017 |publisher=Stuff}}</ref> and, prior to 2011, his father attended [[Didsbury Mosque]].<ref name=\"telegrsalman\" /><ref name=\"guardmosque\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ian Cobain|last2=Frances Perraudin|last3=Steven Morris|last4=Nazia Parveen|title=Salman Ramadan Abedi named by police as Manchester Arena attacker|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|accessdate=27 May 2017|work=The Guardian|quote=Salman and his brother Ismail worshipped at Didsbury mosque, where their father, who is known as Abu Ismail within the community, is a well-known figure. \"He used to do the five and call the adhan. He has an absolutely beautiful voice. And his boys learned the Qur'an by heart.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526212713/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|archivedate=26 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi attended [[Wellacre Academy|Wellacre Technology College]], [[Burnage Academy for Boys]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Devine |first1=Peter |title=Manchester Arena bomber Salman Abedi was former Wellacre pupil |url=https://www.messengernewspapers.co.uk/news/whereyoulive/15321454.manchester-arena-bomber-salman-abedi-was-former-wellacre-pupil/ |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=Messenger Newspapers |date=1 June 2017}}</ref> and [[The Manchester College]]. A former tutor remarked that Abedi was \"a very slow, uneducated and passive person\".<ref name=GMay26/> According to ''[[The Times]]'', Abedi had been among a group of students at his high school who had accused a teacher of [[Islamophobia]] for asking them what they thought of suicide bombers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dearden|first1=Lizzie|title=Salman Abedi once called RE teacher an 'Islamophobe' for asking his opinion of suicide bombers|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salman-abedi-re-teacher-islamophobe-suicide-bombers-burnage-academy-for-boys-opinion-manchester-a7756611.html|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=The Independent|date=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606082916/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salman-abedi-re-teacher-islamophobe-suicide-bombers-burnage-academy-for-boys-opinion-manchester-a7756611.html|archivedate=6 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Simpson|first1=John|last2=Gibbons|first2=Katie|last3=Kenber|first3=Billy|last4=Trew|first4=Bel|title=Abedi called teacher an Islamophobe|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/killer-called-teacher-an-islamophobe-v9tgnkxd0|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=[[The Times]]|date=26 May 2017}}</ref> He also reportedly said to his friends that being a suicide bomber 'was ok' and fellow college students raised concerns about his behaviour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-banned-13092209|title=Salman Abedi banned from mosque and reported to authorities for extremist views|last=Fox|first=Aine|date=25 May 2017|work=Manchester Evening News|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAbedi's father was a member of the [[Libyan Islamic Fighting Group]], a Salafi jihadist organisation proscribed by the United Nations,<ref name=\"un1267\">{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sc/committees/1267/NSQE01101E.shtml |title=QE.L.11.01. Libyan Islamic Fighting Group |publisher=[[United Nations Security Council Al-Qaida Sanctions Committee]] |date=23 August 2010 |accessdate=9 August 2012}}</ref> and father and son fought for the group in Libya in 2011 as part of the movement to [[Libyan Civil War (2011)|overthrow Muammar Gaddafi]].<ref name=GMay26>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/26/salman-abedi-manchester-arena-attack-partying-suicide-bomber Salman Abedi: from hot-headed party lover to suicide bomber]. ''The Guardian'' (26 May 2017). Retrieved 2018-10-26.</ref> Abedi's parents, both born in [[Tripoli]], remained in Libya in 2011,<ref name=\"telegrsalman\" /> while 17-year-old Abedi returned to live in the United Kingdom. He took a [[gap year]] in 2014, where he returned with his brother Hashem to Libya to live with his parents. Abedi was injured in [[Ajdabiya]] that year while fighting for an Islamist group.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/28/salman-abedi-manchester-arena-bomber-radicalisation How Manchester bomber Salman Abedi was radicalised by his links to Libya]. ''The Guardian'' (27 May 2017). Retrieved 2018-10-26.</ref> The brothers were rescued from Tripoli by the [[Royal Navy]] survey ship {{HMS|Enterprise|H88|6}} in August 2014 as part of a group of 110 British citizens as the [[Libyan Civil War (2014\u2013present)|Libyan civil war]] erupted, taken to [[Malta]] and flown back to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/royal-navy-rescued-manchester-bomber-from-the-libyan-civil-war-11454899|title=Manchester bomber Salman Abedi was rescued from Libyan civil war by Royal Navy|work=[[Sky News]]|date=31 July 2018|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-45021513|title=Did MI5 miss chance to catch Manchester Arena bomber Salman Abedi?|work=[[BBC News]]|date=31 July 2018|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> According to a retired European intelligence officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, Abedi met with members of the ISIS Battar brigade in [[Sabratha]], Libya and continued to be in contact with the group upon his return to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Rukmini|last1=Callimachi|first2=Eric|last2=Schmit|title=Manchester bomber met with ISIS unit in Libya, officials say|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/03/world/middleeast/manchester-bombing-salman-abedi-islamic-state-libya.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 June 2017|accessdate=4 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603225742/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/03/world/middleeast/manchester-bombing-salman-abedi-islamic-state-libya.html|archivedate=3 June 2017}}</ref> An [[imam]] at Didsbury mosque recalled that Abedi looked at him \"with hate\" after he preached against [[ISIS]] and [[Ansar al-Sharia (Libya)|Ansar al-Sharia]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cobain|first1=Ian|last2=Perraudin|first2=Frances|last3=Morris|first3=Steven|last4=Parveen|first4=Nazia|title=Salman Ramadan Abedi named by police as Manchester Arena attacker|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|accessdate=24 May 2017|work=The Guardian|date=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524003525/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an acquaintance in the UK, Abedi was \"outgoing\" and consumed alcohol,<ref name=cannabis>{{Cite news|title=Salman Abedi: How Manchester attacker turned from cannabis-smoking dropout to Isis suicide bomber|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salman-abedi-manchester-attacker-isis-terrorist-europe-islamist-suicide-bomber-arena-explosion-a7753541.html|last=Dearden|first=Lizzie|date=24 May 2017|work=The Independent|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819204355/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/salman-abedi-manchester-attacker-isis-terrorist-europe-islamist-suicide-bomber-arena-explosion-a7753541.html|archivedate=19 August 2017}}</ref> while another said that Abedi was a \"regular kid who went out and drank\" until about 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everything we know about Salman Abedi, the Manchester suicide bomber|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/everything-know-salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525235330/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/everything-know-salman-abedi-named-manchester-suicide-bomber/|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi was also known to have used cannabis.<ref name=\"who was salman abedi\" /><ref name=\"cannabis\" />  He enrolled at the [[University of Salford]] in September 2014, where he studied [[business administration]], before dropping out to work in a [[bakery]].<ref name=\"who was salman abedi\" /> Manchester police believe Abedi used [[student loan]]s to finance the plot, including travel overseas to learn bomb-making.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robert Mendick|last2=Martin Evans|last3=Victoria Ward|title=Exclusive: Manchester suicide bomber used student loan and benefits to fund terror plot|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/26/exclusive-manchester-suicide-bomber-used-student-loan-benefits/|accessdate=27 May 2017|work=The Telegraph|quote=The Manchester suicide bomber used taxpayer-funded student loans and benefits to bankroll the terror plot, police believe.  Salman Abedi is understood to have received thousands of pounds in state funding in the run up to Monday's atrocity even while he was overseas receiving bomb-making training.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527010434/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/26/exclusive-manchester-suicide-bomber-used-student-loan-benefits/|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that despite dropping out from further education, he continued to receive student loan funding as recently as April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ian Cobain|last2=Ewen MacAskill|title=Police focus on Libya amid reports of arrest of Salman Abedi's brother|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/manchester-attack-police-focus-on-libya-as-salman-abedi-brother-arrested|accessdate=27 May 2017|work=The Guardian|quote=Abedi studied business and management at Salford University two or three years ago, but dropped out of the course and did not complete his degree. The Guardian understands he was receiving student loan payments as recently as last month.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527033654/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/manchester-attack-police-focus-on-libya-as-salman-abedi-brother-arrested|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi returned to Manchester on 18 May after a trip to Libya and bought bomb-making material, apparently constructing the [[acetone peroxide]]-based bomb by himself. It is known that many members of the ISIS Battar brigade trained people in bomb-making in Libya.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lizzie|last=Dearden|title=Manchester attack: Salman Abedi 'made bomb in four days' after potentially undergoing terror training in Libya|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-attack-bombing-salman-abedi-isis-libya-terror-training-militants-tatp-four-days-bomb-a7771391.html|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]|location=London|date=3 June 2017|accessdate=4 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603185354/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-attack-bombing-salman-abedi-isis-libya-terror-training-militants-tatp-four-days-bomb-a7771391.html|archivedate=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was known to British security services and police but was not regarded as a high risk, having been linked to petty crime but never flagged up for radical views.<ref name=\"guardmosque\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|title=Manchester Arena attacker named by police as Salman Ramadan Abedi|work=The Guardian|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523174251/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/manchester-arena-attacker-named-salman-abedi-suicide-attack-ariana-grande|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/police-reveal-manchester-attacker-salman-abedi-s-petty-criminal-past/story-iALPPyhtag37nTFGbchxhL.html|title=Police reveal Manchester attacker Salman Abedi's petty criminal past|date=30 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530191618/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/police-reveal-manchester-attacker-salman-abedi-s-petty-criminal-past/story-iALPPyhtag37nTFGbchxhL.html|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> A community worker told the BBC he had called a hotline five years before the bombing to warn police about Abedi's views and members of Britain's [[Libyan diaspora]] said they had \"warned authorities for years\" about Manchester's [[Islamism in the United Kingdom|Islamist]] [[radicalisation]].<ref name=\"bbc2504\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stephen|first1=Chris|title=Libyans in UK 'warned about Manchester radicalisation for years'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/libyans-in-uk-warned-about-manchester-radicalisation-for-years|accessdate=25 May 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524222943/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/libyans-in-uk-warned-about-manchester-radicalisation-for-years|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi was allegedly reported to authorities for his [[extremism]] by five community leaders and family members and had been banned from a mosque;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/security-services-missed-five-opportunities-stop-manchester/|title=Security services missed five opportunities to stop the Manchester bomber|newspaper=The Telegraph|first1=Robert|last1=Mendick|first2=Gordon|last2=Rayner|first3=Martin|last3=Evans|first4=Hayley|last4=Dixon|date=25 May 2017|access-date=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526021047/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/24/security-services-missed-five-opportunities-stop-manchester/|archivedate=26 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sharman|first1=Jon|title=Manchester attack: Members of the public 'reported Salman Abedi to anti-terror hotline'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-attack-latest-public-reported-salman-abedi-terrorism-hotline-a7754621.html|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=[[The Independent]]|date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525031417/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-attack-latest-public-reported-salman-abedi-terrorism-hotline-a7754621.html|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Fox|first1=Aine|last2=Abbit|first2=Beth|title=Manchester bomber Salman Abedi was banned from a mosque and reported to authorities for his extremist views|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-banned-13092209|date=25 May 2017|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=Manchester Evening News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525161030/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-banned-13092209|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> the [[Chief Constable of Greater Manchester]], though, said Abedi was not known to the [[CONTEST#Prevent|Prevent]] anti-radicalisation programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/30/salman-abedi-unknown-prevent-workers-manchester-police|title=Salman Abedi was unknown to Prevent workers, says police chief|last=Perraudin|first=Frances|work=The Guardian|date=30 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530191024/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/30/salman-abedi-unknown-prevent-workers-manchester-police|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2017, [[MI5]] launched an internal inquiry into its handling of the warnings it had received about Abedi and a second, \"more in depth\" inquiry, into how it missed the danger.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/05/29/europe/mi5-internal-inquiry-abedi/ |title=MI5 launches internal inquiry over Manchester bomber warnings |publisher=CNN |date=29 May 2017 |accessdate=29 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605115324/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/05/29/europe/mi5-internal-inquiry-abedi |archivedate=5 June 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-40080646 |title=Manchester attacks: MI5 probes bomber 'warnings' |publisher=BBC News |date=29 May 2017 |accessdate=29 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529065526/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-40080646 |archivedate=29 May 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/28/mi5-launches-inquiries-into-failings-on-manchester-arena-bomber-salman-abedi-moss-side-raids-amber-rudd|title=MI5 opens inquiries into missed warnings over Manchester terror threat|last=Dodd|first=Vikram|date=29 May 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=31 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530172400/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/28/mi5-launches-inquiries-into-failings-on-manchester-arena-bomber-salman-abedi-moss-side-raids-amber-rudd|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> The ''Daily Mail'' reported that MI5 had a policy of allowing Libyans in the UK to travel to fight against Gaddafi and return later, including some who had been under house arrest in the UK for counter-terrorist measures.<ref>Curtis, Mark (5 April 2018). [https://www.middleeasteye.net/columns/what-will-be-blowback-uk-government-after-libya-revelations-1624802462 What will be the blowback for UK government after Libya revelations?]. Middle East Eye. Retrieved 2018-10-26.</ref> On 22 November 2018, the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament]] published a report which said that MI5 had acted \"too slowly\" in its dealings with Abedi. The committee's report noted \"What we can say is that there were a number of a failings in the handling of Salman Abedi's case. While it is impossible to say whether these would have prevented the devastating attack on 22 May, we have concluded that as a result of the failings, potential opportunities to prevent it were missed.\"<ref name=\"BBCreport\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46303812|title=MI5 'too slow' over Manchester Arena bomber|date=22 November 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\n[[File:Manchester bombing.png|thumb|350px|Bombing location map<!-- No period&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;see MOS:CAPFRAG -->]]\nThe property in Fallowfield where Abedi lived was raided on 23 May. Armed police breached the house with a controlled explosion and searched it. Abedi's 23-year-old brother was arrested in [[Chorlton-cum-Hardy]] in south Manchester in relation to the attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-attack-bombing-suspect-named-as-salman-abedi-us-officials-say-a3546576.html|title=Manchester attack: Bombing suspect named as Salman Abedi, police confirm|last=Simpson|first=Fiona|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|location=London|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523173941/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-attack-bombing-suspect-named-as-salman-abedi-us-officials-say-a3546576.html|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"FT-bomber-named\" /> Police carried out raids in two other areas of south Manchester and another address in the Whalley Range area.<ref name=\"FT-bomber-named\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/59ee15dc-3fc5-11e7-82b6-896b95f30f58|title=Manchester suicide bomber named as 22-year-old from city|first1=Sam|last1=Jones|first2=Leila|last2=Haddou|first3=Andrew|last3=Bounds|work=[[Financial Times]]|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606204257/https://www.ft.com/content/59ee15dc-3fc5-11e7-82b6-896b95f30f58|archivedate=6 June 2017}}</ref> Three other men were arrested, and police initially spoke of a network supporting the bomber;<ref name=bbc2504>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40032504|title=Manchester attack: Police hunt 'network' behind bomber|publisher=BBC News|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524144125/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40032504|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> they later announced that Abedi had sourced all the bomb components himself, and that they now believed he had largely acted alone.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/31/police-believe-manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-acted-largely-alone|title=Police believe Manchester bomber Salman Abedi largely acted alone|last=Pidd|first=Helen|date=31 May 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|issn=0261-3077|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531010801/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/31/police-believe-manchester-bomber-salman-abedi-acted-largely-alone|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref> On 6 July, police said that they believed others had been aware of Abedi's plans.<ref name=\"Gdn7717\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jul/06/manchester-bombing-police-believe-salman-abedi-did-not-act-alone|title=Manchester bombing: police say Salman Abedi did not act alone|last=Parveen|first=Nazia|date=7 July 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707012340/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jul/06/manchester-bombing-police-believe-salman-abedi-did-not-act-alone|archivedate=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to German police sources, Abedi transited through [[D\u00fcsseldorf Airport]] on his way home to Manchester from Istanbul four days before the bombing.<ref>{{cite news |last=Huggler |first=Justin |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/25/manchester-bomber-dusseldorf-four-days-attack-german-media-reports/ |title=Manchester bomber passed through Dusseldorf four days before the attack, German media reports |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 May 2017 |accessdate=30 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530061033/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/25/manchester-bomber-dusseldorf-four-days-attack-german-media-reports/ |archivedate=30 May 2017  }}</ref> French interior minister [[G\u00e9rard Collomb]] said in an interview with [[BFM TV]] that Abedi may have been to Syria, and had \"proven\" links with ISIS.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/french-interior-minister-salman-abedi-had-proven-links-with-islamic-state/|first=Saim|last=Saeed|title=French interior minister: Salman Abedi had 'proven' links with Islamic State|work=[[politico.eu]]|date=24 May 2017|access-date=1 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524124439/http://www.politico.eu/article/french-interior-minister-salman-abedi-had-proven-links-with-islamic-state/|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> Abedi's younger brother and father were arrested by [[RADA Special Deterrence Forces|Libyan security forces]] on 23 and 24 May respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-security-manchester-libya-idUSKBN18K28M?il=0|title=Manchester bomber's father says he did not expect attack|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=25 May 2017|access-date=29 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524214731/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-security-manchester-libya-idUSKBN18K28M?il=0|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> The brother was suspected of planning an attack in Libya, and was said to be in regular touch with Salman, and aware of the plan to bomb the Manchester Arena,<ref name=\"WaPo-24-05-2017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/british-prime-minister-raises-nations-threat-level-saying-another-attackmay-be-imminent/2017/05/24/dd5367e8-3fec-11e7-b29f-f40ffced2ddb_story.html|title=Manchester bombing probe expands with arrests on two continents|first1=Griff|last1=Witte|first2=Karla|last2=Adam|first3=Sudarsan|last3=Raghavan|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524074250/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/british-prime-minister-raises-nations-threat-level-saying-another-attackmay-be-imminent/2017/05/24/dd5367e8-3fec-11e7-b29f-f40ffced2ddb_story.html|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> but not the date.<ref name=bbc6102>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40056102|title=Manchester attack: Police make tenth arrest|publisher=BBC News|date=26 May 2017|accessdate=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526071041/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40056102|archivedate=26 May 2017}}</ref> According to a Libyan official, the brothers spoke on the phone about 15 minutes before the attack was carried out.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/26/europe/manchester-terror-attack-uk/index.html|title=Manchester bomber spoke to brother before attack|last=Smith-Spark|first=Laura|last2=Gorani|first2=Hala|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|access-date=26 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526122050/http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/26/europe/manchester-terror-attack-uk/index.html|archivedate=26 May 2017}}</ref> On 1 November 2017, the UK requested Libya to extradite the bomber's younger brother, Hashem Abedi to return to the UK to face trial for complicity in the murder of the 22 people killed in the explosion.<ref name=\"GdnExdradit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/nov/01/uk-requests-extradition-of-hashem-abedi-over-manchester-arena-attack|title=UK requests extradition of Hashem Abedi over Manchester Arena attack|last=Pidd|first=Helen|date=1 November 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=1 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102014449/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/nov/01/uk-requests-extradition-of-hashem-abedi-over-manchester-arena-attack|archivedate=2 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nPhotographs of the remains of the [[Improvised explosive device|IED]] published by ''[[The New York Times]]'' indicated that it had comprised an explosive charge inside a lightweight metal container which was carried within a black vest or a blue [[Karrimor]] backpack. Most of the fatalities occurred in a ring around the bomber. His torso was propelled by the blast through the doors to the arena, possibly indicating that the explosive charge was held in the backpack and blew him forward on detonation. A small device thought to have possibly been a hand-held detonator was also found.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-arena-bomb-materials-photos.html|title=Found at the Scene in Manchester: Shrapnel, a Backpack and a Battery|last=Chivers|first=C.L.|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524174025/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/24/world/europe/manchester-arena-bomb-materials-photos.html|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> US Congressman [[Michael McCaul]], chairman of the [[House Homeland Security Committee]], indicated that the bomb contained the explosive [[acetone peroxide|TATP]], which has been used in previous bombings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/manchester-attack-latest-u-s-lawmaker-says-u-k-bomb-showed-sophistication-1.3426624|title=Manchester attack latest: U.S. lawmaker says U.K. bomb showed 'sophistication'|date=24 May 2017|work=CTVNews|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626030225/http://www.ctvnews.ca/world/manchester-attack-latest-u-s-lawmaker-says-u-k-bomb-showed-sophistication-1.3426624|archivedate=26 June 2017}}</ref> According to Manchester police, the explosive device used by Abedi was the design of a skilled bomb-maker and had a back-up means of detonation.<ref>{{cite news|title=The hunt is on for the Manchester bomber's accomplices|url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21722697-it-seems-salman-abedi-did-not-act-aloneand-his-fellow-plotters-could-strike-again-hunt|accessdate=26 May 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525231928/http://www.economist.com/news/britain/21722697-it-seems-salman-abedi-did-not-act-aloneand-his-fellow-plotters-could-strike-again-hunt|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> Police also said Salman Abedi \"bought most of Manchester bomb components himself\" and that he was alone during much of the time before carrying out the Manchester bombing.<ref name=\"GdnExdradit\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/30/salman-abedi-bought-most-of-manchester-bomb-components-himself-6673508/|title=Salman Abedi 'bought most of Manchester bomb components himself'|first=Jen|last=Mills|work=[[Metro News]]|date=30 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828070730/http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/30/salman-abedi-bought-most-of-manchester-bomb-components-himself-6673508/|archivedate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 May, police released images showing Abedi on the night of the bombing, taken from [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]] footage.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40072786 |title=Manchester attack: CCTV shows bomber before arena blast |publisher=BBC News |date=28 May 2017 |accessdate=29 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528235059/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40072786 |archivedate=28 May 2017  }}</ref> Further images showed Abedi walking around Manchester with a blue suitcase.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/29/europe/mi5-internal-inquiry-abedi/index.html|title=Did you see Manchester bomber with blue suitcase?|last=Roberts|first=Elizabeth|last2=Gast|first2=Phil|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|access-date=31 May 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530211251/http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/29/europe/mi5-internal-inquiry-abedi/index.html|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to US intelligence sources, Abedi was identified by the [[bank card]] that he had with him and the identification confirmed using [[Facial recognition system|facial recognition technology]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/manchester-concert-explosion/manchester-bombing-british-police-release-new-photos-suspect-salman-abedi-n765476|title=British police release new photos of arena bombing suspect|publisher=[[NBC News]]|access-date=27 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527214413/http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/manchester-concert-explosion/manchester-bombing-british-police-release-new-photos-suspect-salman-abedi-n765476|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nA total of 22 people were arrested in connection with the attack, but had all been released without charge by 11 June following the police's conclusion that Abedi was likely to have acted alone, even though others may have been aware of his plans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/those-arrested-manchester-arena-attack-13170282|title=All those arrested since Manchester Arena attack released without charge|last=Cox|first=Charlotte|date=11 June 2017|work=[[Manchester Evening News]]|access-date=17 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611162404/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/those-arrested-manchester-arena-attack-13170282|archivedate=11 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 July 2019, Salman Abedi's brother Hashem was charged with murder, attempted murder and conspiracy to cause an explosion. He had been arrested in Libya and [[Extradition|extradited]] to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/jul/17/hashem-abedi-brother-of-manchester-arena-bomber-being-extradited-to-uk|title=Manchester Arena bomber's brother held in UK after extradition|work=The Guardian|date=17 July 2019|accessdate=18 July 2019}}</ref> His trial began on 5 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-51371530|title=Hashem Abedi: Manchester Arena attack brother 'equally guilty'|date=4 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020|work=BBC News}}</ref> On 17 March, Hashem Abedi was found guilty on 22 charges of murder, on the grounds that he had helped his brother to source the materials used in the bombing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-51926162 |title=Manchester Arena bombing: Hashem Abedi guilty of 22 murders |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=17 March 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===News leaks===\nWithin hours of the attack, Abedi's name and other information given confidentially to security services in the United States and France were [[News leak|leaked to the news media]], leading to condemnation from [[Home Secretary]] [[Amber Rudd]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2017-40026413|title=Manchester attack: US leaks about bomber irritating \u2013 Rudd|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=24 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524114710/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2017-40026413|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref><ref name=leaks>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/us-officials-leak-more-manchester-details-hours-after-uk-rebuke |title=US officials leak more Manchester details hours after UK rebuke |newspaper=The Guardian |date=24 May 2017 |first1=Ewen |last1=MacAskill |first2=Julian |last2=Borger |location=London & Washington |accessdate=24 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524153934/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/24/us-officials-leak-more-manchester-details-hours-after-uk-rebuke |archivedate=24 May 2017  }}</ref> Following the publication of crime scene photographs of the backpack bomb used in the attack in the 24 May edition of ''The New York Times'', UK counterterrorism police chiefs said the release of the material was detrimental to the investigation.<ref name=\"BBC 24 May 2017\">{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40038630|title= Manchester attack: 'Fury' at US 'evidence' photos leak|date= 24 May 2017|publisher= BBC News|accessdate= 24 May 2017|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170524213432/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40038630|archivedate= 24 May 2017|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May, [[Greater Manchester Police]] said it had stopped sharing information on the attack with the US intelligence services. May said she would make clear to [[President Trump]] that \"intelligence that has been shared must be made secure.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40040210|title=Manchester attack: Police 'not sharing information with US'|date=25 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525075547/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-40040210|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> Trump described the leaks to the news media as \"deeply troubling\", and pledged to carry out a full investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40048565|title=Manchester attack: Trump condemns media leaks|date=25 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|access-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525142202/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40048565|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> British officials blamed the leaks on \"the breakdown of normal discipline at the White House and in the US security services\".<ref name=\"GdnWHRift\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/25/white-house-rift-with-security-agencies-aided-manchester-bomb-leaks|title=White House rift with security agencies 'aided Manchester bomb leaks'|first1=Ewen|last1=MacAskill|first2=Julian|last2=Borger|location=London & Washington|date=25 May 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=25 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525194616/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/may/25/white-house-rift-with-security-agencies-aided-manchester-bomb-leaks|archivedate=25 May 2017}}</ref> ''New York Times'' editor [[Dean Baquet]] declined to apologise for publishing the backpack bomb photographs, saying \"We live in different press worlds\" and that the material was not classified at the highest level.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40067421/manchester-attack-editor-defends-publishing-leaked-photos|title=Manchester attack: Editor defends publishing leaked photos|date=27 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|access-date=27 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527011659/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-40067421/manchester-attack-editor-defends-publishing-leaked-photos|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May, US Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson]] said the United States government accepted responsibility for the leaks.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. takes 'full responsibility' for Manchester intelligence leaks \u2013 Tillerson|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-security-manchester-tillerson-idUKKBN18M1E4|accessdate=30 May 2017|agency=Reuters|date=26 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527095429/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-security-manchester-tillerson-idUKKBN18M1E4|archivedate=27 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Links with the Muslim Brotherhood ===\nAccording to a secret recording unveiled by the BBC, Mostafa Graf, the imam of the [[Didsbury Mosque]] where Salman Abedi and his family were regulars, made a call for armed jihad 10 days before Abedi bought his concert ticket.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44729727|title=Mosque sermon 'called for armed jihad'|last=Titheradge|first=Ed Thomas and Noel|date=16 August 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=1 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nFollowing these revelations, the Manchester Police opened an investigation into the mosque and its Imam, who also fought with a Libyan Islamist militia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/aug/16/police-investigate-links-between-arena-bomber-and-manchester-imam|title=Manchester police investigate arena bomber's links to imam|last=Pidd|first=Helen|date=16 August 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref> Mostafa Graf is a member of the International Union of Muslim Scholars, an organisation founded by the Muslim Brotherhood and Yusuf al-Qaradawi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/gulf-qatar/islamist-group-rejects-terrorism-charge-by-states-boycotting-qatar-idUSL8N1O12V8|title=Islamist group rejects terrorism charge by states boycotting Qatar|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=1 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Al-Qaradawi is known for having claimed, \"Suicide bombings are a duty\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/gdpr-consent/|title=- The Washington Post|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nHaras Rafiq, head of the [[Quilliam]] think tank, told ''The Guardian'' that the Muslim Brotherhood runs the Didsbury Mosque.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/28/salman-abedi-manchester-arena-bomber-radicalisation|title=How Manchester bomber Salman Abedi was radicalised by his links to Libya|last=Doward|first=Jamie|last2=Cobain|first2=Ian|date=28 May 2017|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018|last3=Stephen|first3=Chris|last4=Quinn|first4=Ben}}</ref>\n\nThe Didsbury Mosque is controlled by The Islamic Centre (Manchester), an English association headed by Dr. Haytham al-Khaffaf, who is also a director of the Human Relief Foundation, a Muslim Brotherhood organisation blacklisted for terrorism by Israel.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beta.charitycommission.gov.uk/charity-details/?regid=327235&subid=0|title=Charity Details|website=beta.charitycommission.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/a-shadowy-web-traced-back-to-bradford-bzxshhbrz9z|title=A shadowy web traced back to Bradford|last=Norfolk|first=Andrew|date=17 August 2015|work=The Times|access-date=1 October 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> Between 2015 and 2016, al-Khaffaf's Human Relief Foundation received over \u00a31.5 million from the Qatar Charity, which is also subject of US counterterrorism surveillance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/06195282/filing-history|title=HUMAN RELIEF FOUNDATION \u2013 Filing history (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|page=see page 24 in the Group of companies' accounts made up to 31 December 2016|language=en|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=12 May 2009|title=Qatar Commits Usd 40 Million for Un Operations in Gaza|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09DOHA314_a.html|journal=WikiLeaks|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n{{Main|Reactions to the Manchester Arena bombing}}\n\n===United Kingdom===\n[[File:St Ann's Square floral tribute panorama (02).jpg|thumb|Floral tributes to the victims of the attack in [[St Ann's Square, Manchester|St Ann's Square]] in Manchester city centre<!-- No period&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;see MOS:CAPFRAG -->]]\n<!-- PLEASE ADD ANY FURTHER CONDOLENCES TO THE DAUGHTER ARTICLE, WHERE THEY BELONG -->\nMay condemned the bombing,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/theresa-may-leads-condemnation-of-cowardly-manchester-attack|title=Theresa May leads condemnation of 'cowardly' Manchester attack|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=23 May 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=31 May 2017|url-status=live|last2=Elgot|first2=Jessica|issn=0261-3077|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531063101/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/may/23/theresa-may-leads-condemnation-of-cowardly-manchester-attack|archivedate=31 May 2017}}</ref> and in a later statement following the [[June 2017 London Bridge attack|June 2017 London attack]], she stated that these attacks along with the [[2017 Westminster attack]] were \"bound together by the single evil ideology of Islamist extremism\" and said this extremism was \"a perversion of Islam\".<ref name=\"MayJune04\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/britain-security-may-statement-idUSL8N1J10GH|title=TEXT-UK Prime Minister May's statement following London attack|date=4 June 2017|agency=Reuters|access-date=5 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604150824/http://www.reuters.com/article/britain-security-may-statement-idUSL8N1J10GH|archivedate=4 June 2017}}</ref> [[Queen Elizabeth II]] expressed her sympathy to the families of the victims.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.royal.uk/message-her-majesty-queen-lord-lieutenant-greater-manchester|title=A message from Her Majesty The Queen to the Lord-Lieutenant of Greater Manchester|last=Jenny.minard|date=23 May 2017|work=The Royal Family|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523132220/https://www.royal.uk/message-her-majesty-queen-lord-lieutenant-greater-manchester|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> Campaigning for [[2017 United Kingdom general election|the general election]] was suspended by all political parties for two days after the attack.<ref name=\"ITV News GE2017\">{{cite news | title=Campaigning suspended as world leaders pay respects | website=ITV News | date=23 May 2017 | url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-23/campaigning-suspended-as-world-leaders-pay-respects/ | accessdate=23 May 2017 | quote=Leaders of political parties did not hesitate to suspend General Election campaigning in the wake of the terror attack in Manchester. ... Campaigning for the 8 June vote will remain suspended for a second day on Wednesday. | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523231153/http://www.itv.com/news/update/2017-05-23/campaigning-suspended-as-world-leaders-pay-respects/ | archivedate=23 May 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"GECampaign\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/23/general-election-campaigning-suspended-after-manchester-attack|title=General election campaigning suspended after Manchester attack|date=22 May 2017|work=The Guardian|location=London|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523040412/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/may/23/general-election-campaigning-suspended-after-manchester-attack|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> The [[Mayor of Greater Manchester]], [[Andy Burnham]], called the attack \"evil\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-attack-mayor-andy-burnham-says-spirit-of-manchester-will-prevail-after-evil-act-a3545916.html|title=Andy Burnham says spirit of Manchester will prevail after 'evil act'|date=23 May 2017|work=London Evening Standard|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523095334/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/manchester-attack-mayor-andy-burnham-says-spirit-of-manchester-will-prevail-after-evil-act-a3545916.html|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> and announced a vigil in [[Albert Square, Manchester|Albert Square]] the following evening,<ref name=\"updates bbc\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-england-manchester-40007967|title=Manchester Arena explosion: Latest updates|date=23 May 2017|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523070932/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-england-manchester-40007967|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> which thousands attended.<ref name=\"corbyn\">{{cite web|last1=Edwards|first1=Peter|title=Corbyn attends Manchester vigil and insists: \"Our hearts are broken but our resolve has never been stronger\"|url=https://labourlist.org/2017/05/corbyn-attends-manchester-vigil-and-insists-our-hears-are-broken-but-our-resolve-has-never-been-stronger/|website=Labour List|accessdate=24 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708224003/https://labourlist.org/2017/05/corbyn-attends-manchester-vigil-and-insists-our-hears-are-broken-but-our-resolve-has-never-been-stronger/|archivedate=8 July 2017}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/nick-ferrari/manchester-mayor-bomber-was-a-terrorist-not-muslim/ Manchester Mayor: Bomber Was A Terrorist, Not A Muslim] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605062343/http://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/nick-ferrari/manchester-mayor-bomber-was-a-terrorist-not-muslim/ |date=5 June 2017 }}, lbc.co.uk, 24 May 2017</ref> The [[Muslim Council of Britain]] also condemned the attack.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-arena-bombing-everything-we-know-suicide-attack-killed-injured-ariana-grande-concert-isis-a7751031.html | title=Manchester Arena bombing: Everything we know about the suicide attack that killed at least 22 people | work=The Independent | date=23 May 2017 | accessdate=23 May 2017 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523131020/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/manchester-arena-bombing-everything-we-know-suicide-attack-killed-injured-ariana-grande-concert-isis-a7751031.html | archivedate=23 May 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May 2017, a national [[minute's silence]] was observed to remember the victims.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40041473 |title=Manchester attack: National minute's silence held |publisher=BBC News |date=25 May 2017 |accessdate=26 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526084023/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-40041473 |archivedate=26 May 2017  }}</ref>\n\nPolice reported a 500% increase in anti-Muslim hate crimes in the Greater Manchester area in the month following the attack.<ref name=\"Gdn22617\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/22/islamophobic-attacks-manchester-increase-arena-attack|title=Islamophobic attacks in Manchester surge by 500% after arena attack|last=Halliday|first=Josh|date=22 June 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707155802/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jun/22/islamophobic-attacks-manchester-increase-arena-attack|archivedate=7 July 2017}}</ref> The [[Commission for Countering Extremism]] was created in the aftermath of the bombing.<ref name=\"PeckExtremism\">{{cite news|last1=Peck|first1=Tom|title=Theresa May to set up commission for countering extremism|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/theresa-may-conservative-manchester-attack-general-election-2017-commission-countering-extremism-a7759486.html|accessdate=18 March 2018|publisher=The Independent|date=27 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===International===\n{{tweet\n|text =           broken. from the bottom of my heart, i am so so sorry. i don't have words.\n|name =           Ariana Grande\n|username =       ArianaGrande \n|date =           23 May 2017 \n|ID =             866849021519966208 \n|reference =      <ref name=\"Ariana tweet\">{{cite tweet |author-link=Ariana Grande |user=ArianaGrande |number=866849021519966208 |date=23 May 2017 |title=broken. from the bottom of my heart, i am so so sorry. i don't have words. |link=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/866849021519966208 |access-date=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n<!-- PLEASE DON'T ADD QUOTES OF CONDOLENCE HERE!!!!! -->\nCondolences were expressed by the leaders and governments of dozens of countries,<ref name=\"Palazzo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/manchester-arena-shock-disbelief-police-confirm-19-killed-terrorist/|title='An attack on innocents': World reacts with shock and horror to Manchester explosion|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=23 May 2017|last=Palazzo|first=Chiara|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523041942/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/manchester-arena-shock-disbelief-police-confirm-19-killed-terrorist/|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> United Nations [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary-General]] [[Ant\u00f3nio Guterres]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=56819|title=UN chief strongly condemns terrorist attack on Manchester concert|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523172429/http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=56819|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> [[Commonwealth Secretary-General]] [[Patricia Scotland]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thecommonwealth.org/media/news/statement-commonwealth-secretary-general-patricia-scotland-terror-attack-manchester|title=Statement by Commonwealth Secretary-General Patricia Scotland on terror attack in Manchester|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012082317/http://thecommonwealth.org/media/news/statement-commonwealth-secretary-general-patricia-scotland-terror-attack-manchester|archivedate=12 October 2017}}</ref> [[President of the European Commission]] [[Jean-Claude Juncker]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_STATEMENT-17-1434_en.htm|title=Statement by European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker following the attack in Manchester|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523072734/http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_STATEMENT-17-1434_en.htm|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref> [[Pope Francis]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/pope-francis-offers-condolences-for-manchester-attack-victims/|title=Pope Francis offers condolences to Manchester attack victims|work=Catholic Herald|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524092012/http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2017/05/23/pope-francis-offers-condolences-for-manchester-attack-victims/|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref> and secretary general of the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation]] [[Yousef Al-Othaimeen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oic-oci.org/topic/?t_id=13607&t_ref=5926&lan=en|title=OIC Secretary General Condemns the Deadly Attack in Manchester, the United Kingdom|date=23 May 2017|accessdate=23 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAriana Grande posted on Twitter: \"broken. from the bottom of my heart, i am so so sorry. i don't have words. [''sic'']\"<ref name=\"Ariana tweet\" /> The tweet briefly became the most-liked tweet in history.<ref>Bloom, Ester. [https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/15/obamas-charlottesville-response-could-be-the-most-popular-tweet-ever.html \"Obama's response to Charlottesville is now the most 'liked' tweet of all time\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816111414/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/15/obamas-charlottesville-response-could-be-the-most-popular-tweet-ever.html |date=16 August 2017 }}, CNBC, 15 August 2017</ref> Grande suspended her tour and flew back to her mother's home in Florida.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ariana-grande-suspends-tour-after-manchester-attack-w483880|title=Ariana Grande Suspends Tour After Manchester Attack|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523212900/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ariana-grande-suspends-tour-after-manchester-attack-w483880|archivedate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ariana-grande-returns-home-to-florida-after-manchester-attack-w483730|title=Ariana Grande Returns Home to Florida After Manchester Concert Attack|work=US Weekly|accessdate=23 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524170722/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ariana-grande-returns-home-to-florida-after-manchester-attack-w483730|archivedate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 July 2017, a performance to benefit the Manchester bombing victims was held in New York City's [[The Cutting Room]], called \"Break Free: United for Manchester\", with Broadway theatre and television performers interpreting Ariana Grande songs.<ref>[http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/BREAK-FREE-Broadway-Performers-to-Throw-Benefit-Concert-for-Manchester-Victims-20170629 \"Break Free: Broadway Performers to Throw Manchester Benefit Concert\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809170833/http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/BREAK-FREE-Broadway-Performers-to-Throw-Benefit-Concert-for-Manchester-Victims-20170629 |date=9 August 2017 }}, BroadwayWorld.com, 29 June 2017</ref>\n\n===One Love Manchester===\n{{Main|One Love Manchester}}\nOn 4 June, Ariana Grande hosted a [[benefit concert]] in Manchester, entitled \"One Love Manchester\" at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground]] that was broadcast live on television, radio and social media. At the concert, Grande performed along with several other high-profile artists. Free tickets were offered to those who had attended the show on 22 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40086336|title=Manchester attack: Ariana Grande to play benefit concert on Sunday|publisher=BBC News|date=30 May 2017|access-date=30 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530153707/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-40086336|archivedate=30 May 2017}}</ref> The benefit concert and associated Red Cross fund raised \u00a310&nbsp;million for victims of the attack by early June<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-40153433|title=One Love Manchester: Joy shines through pain at benefit concert|last=Youngs| first=Ian|date=5 June 2017|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=17 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607021042/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-40153433|archivedate=7 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4805251/ariana-grande-manchester-benefit-concert-fundraising| title=Ariana Grande's Manchester Benefit Concert Raised $13 Million|last=TIME|website=Time| access-date=6 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605221041/http://time.com/4805251/ariana-grande-manchester-benefit-concert-fundraising|archivedate=5 June 2017}}</ref> and \u00a317&nbsp;million by August.<ref>Blistein, Jon. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/families-of-ariana-grande-concert-attack-victims-to-receive-324000-w498012 \"Families of Ariana Grande Concert Attack Victims to Receive $324,000\"], ''Rolling Stone'', 15 August 2017</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''{{'}}s Vulture section ranked the event as the No. 1 concert of 2017.<ref name=Vulture2017>Lockett, Dee. [http://www.vulture.com/2017/12/the-10-best-concerts-of-2017.html \"The 10 Best Concerts of 2017\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222044700/http://www.vulture.com/2017/12/the-10-best-concerts-of-2017.html |date=22 December 2017 }}, ''[[New York Magazine]]'', 21 December 2017</ref>\n\n==The Kerslake Report==\nOn 27 March 2018, the Kerslake Report, \"an independent review into the preparedness for, and emergency response to, the Manchester Arena attack on 22nd May 2017\",<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\">{{cite web | title= The Kerslake Report: An independent review into the preparedness for, and emergency response to, the Manchester Arena attack on 22nd May 2017 |url= https://www.kerslakearenareview.co.uk/media/1022/kerslake_arena_review_printed_final.pdf | author1= Bob Kerslake|author2= Independent panel members |date= 27 March 2018| website= www.kerslakearenareview.co.uk| publisher= | accessdate= 27 March 2018|author1-link= Bob Kerslake }}</ref> was published; it found that the [[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]] was \"brought to a point of paralysis\".<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|5.155}}\n\nThe Kerslake Report \"largely praised\" the [[Greater Manchester Police]] and [[British Transport Police]], and noted that it was \"fortuitous\" that the [[North West Ambulance Service]] was unaware of the declaration of Operation Plato, a protocol under which all responders should have been withdrawn from the arena foyer.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|5.40}}\n\nIt was critical of [[Vodafone]], for the \"catastrophic failure\"<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|5.47}} of an emergency helpline hosted on a platform provided by [[Content Guru]], saying that delays in getting information caused \"significant stress and upset\" to families.<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|17}} It also expressed criticism of some news media, saying, \"To have experienced such intrusive and overbearing behaviour at a time of such enormous vulnerability seemed to us to be completely and utterly unacceptable\",<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|19}} but noting that, \"We recognise that this was some, but by no means all of the media and that the media also have a positive and important role to play.\"<ref name=\"Kerslake Report\"/>{{rp|19}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of terrorist incidents in Great Britain]]\n* [[List of terrorist incidents in May 2017]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Greater Manchester|United Kingdom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|May 2017 Manchester attack}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-40012738 Manchester attack: Who were the victims?] (BBC News)\n*[http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/salman-abedi-manchester-arena-bomber-13601393 The making of a monster: How Manchester boy Salman Abedi became a mass murderer] ''Manchester Evening News'', 19 September 2017\n*[https://www.kerslakearenareview.co.uk/media/1022/kerslake_arena_review_printed_final.pdf The Kerslake Report], March 2018\n\n<!-- Consensus is against adding [[Template:Ariana Grande]]. See talk page consensus headbar. -->\n{{Islamic terrorism in Europe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manchester Arena bombing}}\n[[Category:2010s in Manchester]]\n[[Category:2017 in England]]\n[[Category:2017 murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ariana Grande]]\n[[Category:Attacks on music venues]]\n[[Category:Improvised explosive device bombings in England]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorism in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Islamic terrorist incidents in 2017]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2017]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in England]]\n[[Category:May 2017 crimes in Europe]]\n[[Category:May 2017 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Murder in Manchester]]\n[[Category:Stadium disasters]]\n[[Category:Suicide bombings in 2017]]\n[[Category:Suicide bombings in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in the United Kingdom in 2017]]\n", "name_user": "2601:442:4480:2a80:c4f8:7a45:954c:8f3c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manchester_Arena_bombing"}
{"title_page": "Athanasius Kircher", "text_new": "{{short description|German Jesuit scholar}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| name        = Athanasius Kircher, S.J.\n| image       = Athanasius Kircher.jpg\n| caption     = Portrait of Kircher at age 53<br/>from ''Mundus Subterraneus'' (1664)\n| order        = [[Society of Jesus]]\n| ordination   = 1628\n| birth_date  = 2 May 1602\n| birth_place = [[Geisa]], [[Imperial Abbey]] of [[Fulda monastery|Fulda]], [[Holy Roman Empire]]\n| death_date  = {{d-da|28 November 1680|2 May 1602}}\n| death_place = [[Rome]], [[Papal States]]\n| ethnicity   = German\n| religion    = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| works       = Priest, scholar and scientist <ref name=\"Woods\">Woods, p 4, 109</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Athanasius Kircher''', [[Society of Jesus|S.J.]] (sometimes erroneously spelled '''Kirchner'''; {{lang-la|Athanasius Kircherus}}, 2 May 1602 \u2013 28 November 1680) was a [[German people|German]] [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] [[scholarly method|scholar]] and [[polymath]] who published around 40 major works, most notably in the fields of [[comparative religion]], [[geology]], and [[medicine]]. Kircher has been compared to fellow Jesuit [[Roger Boscovich]] and to [[Leonardo da Vinci]] for his enormous range of interests, and has been honoured with the title \"Master of a Hundred Arts\".<ref name=\"Woods108\">Woods, p 108</ref> He taught for more than forty years at the [[Roman College]], where he set up a [[wunderkammer]]. A resurgence of interest in Kircher has occurred within the scholarly community in recent decades.\n\nKircher claimed to have deciphered the [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|hieroglyphic writing]] of the ancient [[Egyptian language]], but most of his assumptions and translations in this field were later found to be incorrect. He did, however, correctly establish the link between the ancient Egyptian and the [[Coptic language|Coptic]] languages, and some commentators regard him as the founder of [[Egyptology]]. Kircher was also fascinated with [[Sinology]] and wrote an encyclopedia of [[China]], in which he noted the early presence there of [[Nestorian Christians]] while also attempting to establish links with Egypt and Christianity.\n\nKircher's work in geology included studies of [[volcano]]es and [[fossil]]s. One of the first people to observe microbes through a [[microscope]], Kircher was ahead of his time in proposing that the [[Black Death|plague]] was caused by an infectious [[microorganism]] and in suggesting effective measures to prevent the spread of the disease. Kircher also displayed a keen interest in technology and mechanical inventions; inventions attributed to him include a magnetic clock, various [[automaton]]s and the first [[megaphone]]. The invention of the [[magic lantern]] is often misattributed to Kircher,<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Athanasius-Kircher |title=Athanasius Kircher |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Britannica Online |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |access-date=June 4, 2016 }}</ref> although he did conduct a study of the principles involved in his ''Ars Magna Lucis et Umbrae''.\n\nA scientific star in his day, towards the end of his life he was eclipsed by the [[rationalism]] of [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]] and others. In the late 20th century, however, the [[aesthetic]] qualities of his work again began to be appreciated. One modern scholar, Alan Cutler, described Kircher as \"a giant among seventeenth-century scholars\", and \"one of the last thinkers who could rightfully claim all knowledge as his domain\".<ref>Cutler, p 68 <!--quoted by Woods, p 109--></ref> Another scholar, Edward W. Schmidt, referred to Kircher as \"the last [[Polymath|Renaissance man]]\". In ''[[A Man of Misconceptions]],'' his 2012 book about Kircher, John Glassie writes that while \"many of Kircher's actual ideas today seem wildly off-base, if not simply bizarre,\"<ref>John Glassie: A Man of Misconceptions: The Life of an Eccentric in an Age of Change. New York, Riverhead, 2012, p xiv.</ref> he was \"a champion of wonder, a man of awe-inspiring erudition and inventiveness,\" whose work was read \"by the smartest minds of the time.\"<ref>Glassie, p xv</ref>\n\n==Life==\nKircher was born on 2 May in either 1601 or 1602 (he himself did not know) in [[Geisa]], [[Buchonia]], near [[Fulda]], currently [[Thuringia]], [[Germany]]. From his birthplace, he took the epithets ''Bucho, Buchonius'' and ''Fuldensis'' which he sometimes added to his name. He attended the Jesuit College in Fulda from 1614 to 1618, when he entered the [[novitiate]] of the Society.\n\nThe youngest of nine children, Kircher studied volcanoes owing to his passion for rocks and eruptions. He was taught [[Hebrew (language)|Hebrew]] by a [[rabbi]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Wo-w2sl6zEC&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Athanasius+Kircher+hebrew&source=bl&ots=W68Jsjgbt7&sig=0VaBQThyueA2L2ZZ4QSEJs0HGNE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=wrAqVbSdNcPasASm44GICQ&ved=0CB8Q6AEwATgK#v=onepage|title=A Study of the Life and Works of Athanasius Kircher, \u2018Germanus Incredibilis\u2019: With a Selection of His Unpublished Correspondence and an Annotated Translation of His Autobiography.|last=Fletcher|first=John Edward|date=2011-08-25|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004207120|language=en}}</ref> in addition to his studies at school. He studied [[philosophy]] and [[theology]] at [[Paderborn]],<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Athanasius-Kircher |title=Athanasius Kircher |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Britannica Online |publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |access-date=June 4, 2016 }}</ref> but fled to [[Cologne]] in 1622 to escape advancing [[Protestant]] forces. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} On the journey, he narrowly escaped death after falling through the ice crossing the frozen [[Rhine]] \u2014 one of several occasions on which his life was endangered. Later, traveling to [[Heilbad Heiligenstadt|Heiligenstadt]], he was caught and nearly [[hanging|hanged]] by a party of Protestant soldiers. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}\n\nFrom 1622 to 1624 Kircher was sent to begin his [[regency (Jesuit)|regency]] period in [[Koblenz]] as a teacher. This was followed by his assignment to [[Heilbad Heiligenstadt|Heiligenstadt]], where he taught [[mathematics]], Hebrew and [[Aramaic language|Syriac]], and produced a show of [[firework]]s and moving scenery for the visiting [[Prince-Elector|Elector]] [[Archbishop of Mainz]], showing early evidence of his interest in [[mechanics|mechanical devices]]. He was [[Holy Orders|ordained]] to the [[Catholic priest|priesthood]] in 1628<ref name=\"Britannica\"/> and became professor of [[ethics]] and [[mathematics]] at the [[University of W\u00fcrzburg]], where he also taught Hebrew and Syriac. Beginning in 1628, he also began to show an interest in Egyptian hieroglyphs.\n\nIn 1631, while still at [[W\u00fcrzburg]], Kircher allegedly had a prophetic vision of bright light and armed men with horses in the city. Wurzburg was shortly afterwards attacked and captured, leading to Kircher being accorded respect for predicting the disaster via astrology, though Kircher himself privately insisted that he had not relied on that art.<ref>Newman & Grafton, 1-2</ref> This was the year that Kircher published his first book (the ''[[Ars Magnesia]]'', reporting his research on [[magnetism]]), but having been caught up in the [[Thirty Years' War]] he was driven to the papal [[University of Avignon]] in [[France]]. In 1633 he was called to [[Vienna]] by the [[Ferdinand II, Holy Roman Emperor|emperor]] to succeed [[Johannes Kepler|Kepler]] as Mathematician to the [[Habsburg]] court. On the intervention of [[Nicolas-Claude Fabri de Peiresc]], the order was rescinded, and he was sent instead to [[Rome]] to continue with his scholarly work, but he had already embarked for Vienna.\n\nOn the way, his ship was blown off course and he arrived in Rome before he knew of the changed decision. He based himself in the city for the rest of his life, and from 1634<ref>Fletcher 2011, p. 31.</ref> he taught mathematics, [[physics]] and [[Oriental language]]s at the Collegio Romano (now the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]]) for several years before being released to devote himself to research. He studied [[malaria]] and the [[Black Death|plague]], amassing a collection of [[Archaeology|antiquities]], which he exhibited along with devices of his own creation in the Museum Kircherianum.\n\nIn 1661, Kircher discovered the ruins of a [[Church (building)|church]] said to have been constructed by [[Constantine I of the Roman Empire|Constantine]] on the site of [[Saint Eustace]]'s vision of [[Jesus Christ]] in a stag's horns. He raised money to pay for the church's reconstruction as the ''Santuario della Mentorella'', and his heart was buried in the church on his death.\n\n{{anchor|Published work}}\n\n==Works==\n[[File:Latium.tif|thumb|''Latium'', 1671]]\nKircher published a large number of substantial books on a very wide variety of subjects, such as [[Egyptology]], [[geology]], and [[music theory]]. His [[Syncretism|syncretic]] approach disregarded the boundaries between disciplines which are now conventional: his ''Magnes'', for example, was ostensibly a discussion of [[magnetism]], but also explored other forms of attraction such as [[gravity]] and [[love]]. Perhaps Kircher's best-known work today is his ''[[Oedipus Aegyptiacus]]'' (1652\u201354), a vast study of Egyptology and [[comparative religion]].<ref name=\"Kircher, Athanasius 2008\">\"Kircher, Athanasius.\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica from ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica 2007 Ultimate Reference Suite''. (2008).</ref>\n\nHis books, written in [[Latin]], were widely circulated in the 17th century, and they contributed to the dissemination of scientific information to a broader circle of readers. Kircher is not now considered to have made any significant original contributions, although a number of discoveries and inventions (e.g., the [[magic lantern]]) have sometimes been mistakenly attributed to him.<ref name=\"Kircher, Athanasius 2008\"/>\n\nIn his foreword to ''Ars Magna Sciendi Sive Combinatoria'' (The Great Art of Knowledge, or the Combinatorial Art), the inscription reads:<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C5mqDgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA565&ots=sW_IReVdqd&dq=Athanasius%20Kircher%20und%20seine%20erste%20Prager%20Korrespondenz&pg=PA35#v=snippet&q=Athanasius%20Kircher&f=false|page=35|title=Unsolved! The History and Mystery of the World's Greatest Ciphers from Ancient Egypt to Online Secret Societies|author=Craig P. Bauer|year=2010|ISBN=9780691167671|publisher=Princeton University Press}}</ref>\n{{Quote|\"Nothing is more beautiful than to know all.\"}}\n\n===Linguistic and cultural studies===\n====Egyptology====\n{{further|Oedipus Aegyptiacus|Decipherment of ancient Egyptian scripts}}\n\n[[File:Athanasius Kircher Koptisches Alphabet.jpg|thumb|The [[Coptic language|Coptic]] alphabet, from ''Prodromus coptus sive aegyptiacus''.]]\nThe [[Graffito of Esmet-Akhom|last known example]] of [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|Egyptian hieroglyphics]] dates from AD 394, after which all knowledge of hieroglyphics was lost.<ref name=\"Frimmer37\">Frimmer, p 37</ref> Until [[Thomas Young (scientist)|Thomas Young]] and [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Champollion]] found the key to hieroglyphics in the 19th century, the main authority was the 4th-century Greek grammarian [[Horapollon]], whose chief contribution was the misconception that hieroglyphics were \"picture writing\" and that future translators should look for symbolic meaning in the pictures.<ref>Frimmer, pp 37\u201339</ref>\n\nThe first modern study of hieroglyphics came with [[Piero Valeriano Bolzani]]'s ''Hieroglyphica'' (1556),<ref name=\"Frimmer37\"/> and Kircher was the most famous of the \"decipherers\" between ancient and modern times and the most famous Egyptologist of his day.<ref name=\"Frimmer38\">Frimmer, p 38</ref> In his ''Lingua Aegyptiaca Restituta'' (1643), Kircher called hieroglyphics \"this language hitherto unknown in Europe, in which there are as many pictures as letters, as many riddles as sounds, in short as many mazes to be escaped from as mountains to be climbed\".<ref name=\"Frimmer38\"/> While some of his notions are long discredited, portions of his work have been valuable to later scholars, and Kircher helped pioneer Egyptology as a field of serious study.\n\nKircher's interest in Egyptology began in 1628 when he became intrigued by a collection of hieroglyphs in the library at [[Speyer]]. He learned [[Coptic language|Coptic]] in 1633 and published the first grammar of that language in 1636, the ''Prodromus coptus sive aegyptiacus''. Kircher then broke with Horapollon's interpretation of the language of the hieroglyphs with his ''Lingua aegyptiaca restituta''. Kircher argued that Coptic preserved the last development of [[Egyptian language|ancient Egyptian]].<ref name=\"Frimmer38\"/><ref name=\"Woods109\">Woods, p 109</ref> For this Kircher has been considered the true \"founder of Egyptology\", because his work was conducted \"before the discovery of the [[Rosetta Stone]] rendered Egyptian hieroglyphics comprehensible to scholars\".<ref name=\"Woods109\"/> He also recognized the relationship between [[hieratic]] and hieroglyphic scripts.\n\n[[File:oed-aegyp.png|Oedipus Aegyptiacus|thumb|[[Book frontispiece|Frontispiece]] to Kircher's ''Oedipus \u00c6gyptiacus''; the [[Sphinx]], confronted by Kircher's learning, admits he has solved her [[riddle]].]]\n\nBetween 1650 and 1654, Kircher published four volumes of \"translations\" of hieroglyphs in the context of his Coptic studies.<ref name=\"Frimmer38\"/> However, according to Steven Frimmer, \"none of them even remotely fitted the original texts\".<ref name=\"Frimmer38\"/> In ''[[Oedipus Aegyptiacus]]'', Kircher argued under the impression of the ''[[Hieroglyphica]]'' that [[Egyptian language|ancient Egyptian]] was the language spoken by [[Adam and Eve]], that [[Hermes Trismegistus]] was [[Moses]], and that hieroglyphs were [[occult]] [[symbol]]s which \"cannot be translated by words, but expressed only by marks, characters and figures.\" This led him to translate simple hieroglyphic texts now known to read as ''\u1e0fd Wsr'' (\"Osiris says\") as \"The treachery of Typhon ends at the throne of Isis; the moisture of nature is guarded by the vigilance of Anubis\"<ref>for such translations, see e.g. his ''Sphinx mystagoga'', p. 49.</ref>\n\nAccording to the Egyptologist Sir [[E. A. Wallis Budge]]:\n\n{{quote|Many writers pretended to have found the key to the hieroglyphics, and many more professed, with a shameless impudence which is hard to understand in these days, to translate the contents of the texts into a modern tongue. Foremost among such pretenders must be mentioned Athanasius Kircher, who, in the 17th century, declared that he had found the key to the hieroglyphic inscriptions; the translations which he prints in his ''Oedipus Aegyptiacus'' are utter nonsense, but as they were put forth in a learned tongue many people at the time believed they were correct.<ref name=\"Budge\">{{cite book |title=Egyptian Language: Easy Lessons in Egyptian Hieroglyphics |last= Budge |first= E. A. Wallis |authorlink=E. A. Wallis Budge |year=1983 |origyear=1910 |publisher=Dover |location=Mineola, NY |isbn= |page=15 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UmfvHfve6KYC}}</ref>}}\n\nAlthough Kircher's approach to deciphering texts was based on a fundamental misconception, some modern commentators have described Kircher as the pioneer of the serious study of hieroglyphs. The data which he collected were later consulted by [[Champollion]] in his successful efforts to decode the script. According to Joseph MacDonnell, it was \"because of Kircher's work that scientists knew what to look for when interpreting the Rosetta stone\".<ref>MacDonnell, p 12 <!--quoted by Woods, p 109--></ref> Another scholar of ancient Egypt, Erik Iversen, concluded:\n{{Blockquote|It is, therefore, Kircher's incontestable merit that he was the first to have discovered the phonetic value of an Egyptian hieroglyph. From a humanistic as well as an intellectual point of view Egyptology may very well be proud of having Kircher as its founder.<ref>Iversen, pp 97\u201398 <!--quoted by Woods, p 109; via MacDonnell, p 12--></ref>}}\n\nKircher was also actively involved in the erection of [[List of obelisks in Rome|obelisks in Roman squares]], often adding fantastic \"hieroglyphs\" of his design in the blank areas that are now puzzling to modern scholars.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}} Rowland 2002 concluded that Kircher made use of Pythagorean principles to read hieroglyphs of the Pamphili Obelisk, and used the same form of interpretation when reading scripture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fathom.lib.uchicago.edu/1/777777122590|author=Ingrid D. Rowland|publisher=University of Chicago Library|year=2002|title=Athanasius Kircher and the Egyptian Oedipus}}</ref>\n\n====Sinology====\n[[File:Kircherchinamap.jpg|thumb|350px|Map of China, ''China Illustrata''.]]\n{{see also|Jesuit China missions}}\n\nKircher had an early interest in [[China]], telling his superior in 1629 that he wished to become a [[missionary]] to that country. In 1667 he published a treatise whose full title was  ''China monumentis, qua sacris qua profanis, nec non variis naturae & artis spectaculis, aliarumque rerum memorabilium argumentis illustrata'', and which is commonly known simply as ''[[China Illustrata]]'', i.e. \"China Illustrated\". It was a work of encyclopedic breadth, combining material of unequal quality, from  accurate [[cartography]] to mythical elements, such as a study of [[dragon]]s. The work drew heavily on the reports of Jesuits working in China, in particular [[Michael Boym]]<ref>{{citation|first=Hartmut |last=Walravens |url=http://www.haraldfischerverlag.de/hfv/Digital/walravens.pdf |title=Michael Boym und die Flora Sinensis |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927152210/http://www.haraldfischerverlag.de/hfv/Digital/walravens.pdf |archivedate=2011-09-27 }}</ref> and [[Martino Martini]].\n\n''China Illustrata'' emphasized the Christian elements of Chinese history, both real and imagined: the book noted the early presence of [[Nestorian Christian]]s (with a Latin translation of the [[Nestorian Stele]] of [[Xi'an]] provided by Boym and his Chinese collaborator, Andrew Zheng),<ref name=tuyl>[http://hotgates.stanford.edu/Eyes/library/kircher.pdf ''China Illustrata''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818014556/http://hotgates.stanford.edu/Eyes/library/kircher.pdf |date=August 18, 2011 }}; Modern English translation and preface by Dr Charles D. Van Tuyl</ref> but also claimed that the Chinese were descended from the sons of [[Ham, son of Noah|Ham]], that [[Confucius]] was Hermes Trismegistus/Moses and that the [[Chinese character]]s were abstracted hieroglyphs.\n\nIn Kircher's system, [[ideogram]]s were inferior to hieroglyphs because they referred to specific ideas rather than to mysterious complexes of ideas, while the signs of the [[Maya civilization#Writing system|Maya]] and [[Aztec]]s were yet lower [[pictogram]]s which referred only to objects. [[Umberto Eco]] comments that this idea reflected and supported the ethnocentric European attitude toward Chinese and native American civilizations;\n\n\"China was presented not as an unknown barbarian to be defeated but as a prodigal son who should return to the home of the common father\". (p.&nbsp;69)\n\n====Biblical studies and exegesis====\nIn 1675, he published ''[[Arca No\u00eb]]'', the results of his research on the biblical [[Noah's Ark|Ark of Noah]] \u2014  following the [[Counter-Reformation]], [[Allegorical interpretation of the Bible|allegorical interpretation]] was giving way to the study of the Old Testament as literal truth among Scriptural scholars. Kircher analyzed the dimensions of the Ark; based on the number of species known to him (excluding insects and other forms thought to [[spontaneous generation|arise spontaneously]]), he calculated that overcrowding would not have been a problem. He also discussed the logistics of the Ark voyage, speculating on whether extra livestock was brought to feed carnivores and what the daily schedule of feeding and caring for animals must have been.\n\n====Other cultural work====\nKircher was sent the [[Voynich Manuscript]] in 1666 by [[Johannes Marcus Marci]] in the hope of Kircher being able to decipher it.<ref name=nsa>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nsa.gov/public_info/_files/tech_journals/Voynich_Manuscript_Mysterious.pdf |author=Tiltman, John H. |date=Summer 1967 |title=The Voynich Manuscript: \"The Most Mysterious Manuscript in the World\" |volume=XII |number=3 |accessdate=October 30, 2011 |publisher=NSA Technical Journal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018025101/https://www.nsa.gov/public_info/_files/tech_journals/Voynich_Manuscript_Mysterious.pdf |archivedate=October 18, 2011 }}</ref> The manuscript remained in the Collegio Romano until [[Victor Emmanuel II of Italy]] annexed the [[Papal States]] in 1870, though scepticism as to the authenticity of the story and of the origin of the manuscript itself exists.  In his ''Polygraphia nova'' (1663), Kircher proposed an artificial [[universal language]].\n\n===Physical sciences===\n====Geology====\n[[File:Kircherearthfires.jpg|thumb|250px|Kircher's model of the [[Earth]]'s internal fires, from ''Mundus Subterraneus''.]]\n\nOn a visit to [[southern Italy]] in 1638, the ever-curious Kircher was lowered into the [[Volcano|crater]] of [[Vesuvius]], then on the brink of eruption, to examine its interior. He was also intrigued by the subterranean rumbling which he heard at the [[Strait of Messina]]. His geological and geographical investigations culminated in his ''[[Mundus Subterraneus (book)|Mundus Subterraneus]]'' of 1664, in which he suggested that the [[tide]]s were caused by water moving to and from a subterranean [[ocean]].\n\nKircher was also puzzled by [[fossil]]s. He understood that fossils were the remains of animals. He ascribed large bones to giant races of humans.<ref>Palmer, Douglas (2005) Earth Time: Exploring the Deep Past from Victorian England to the Grand Canyon. Wiley, Chichester. {{ISBN|978-0-470-02221-4}}</ref> Not all the objects which he was attempting to explain were in fact fossils, hence the diversity of explanations. He interpreted mountain ranges as the Earth's skeletal structures exposed by weathering.<ref>''The Earth'' \u2013 Richard Fortey, Harper Perennial 2004</ref>\n\n[[File:Athanasius Kircher's Atlantis.gif|thumb|250px| Kircher's map of [[Atlantis]], oriented with south at the top, from ''Mundus Subterraneus''.]]\n\n''Mundus Subterraneus'' includes several pages about the legendary island of [[Atlantis]] including a map with the Latin caption \"Situs Insulae Atlantidis, a Mari olim absorpte ex mente Egyptiorum et Platonis descriptio.\" translating as \"Site of the island of Atlantis, in the sea, from Egyptian sources and Plato's description.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Map of the lost island of Atlantis|url=https://www.raremaps.com/gallery/detail/20754|work=raremaps.com|accessdate=16 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Biology====\nIn his book ''[[Arca No\u00eb]]'', Kircher argued that after the Flood new species were transformed as they moved into different environments, for example, when a [[deer]] moved into a colder climate, it became a [[reindeer]]. Additionally, he held that many species were hybrids of other species, for example, [[armadillo]]s from a combination of [[turtle]]s and [[porcupine]]s. He also advocated the theory of [[spontaneous generation]].<ref>O Breidbach, MT Ghiselin (2006) Athanasius Kircher (1602\u20131680) on Noah's Ark: Baroque \"Intelligent Design\" Theory, Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Volume 57, No. 36, pp. 991\u20131002 <{{cite web|url=http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/scipubs/pdfs/v57/proccas_v57_n36.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009153435/http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/scipubs/pdfs/v57/proccas_v57_n36.pdf |archivedate=2011-10-09 }}></ref> Because of such hypotheses, some historians have held that Kircher was a proto-evolutionist.<ref>Fairfield Osborn, Henry (1902) From the Greeks to Darwin: An Outline of the Development of the Evolution Idea. MacMillan: London, page 106</ref>\n\n====Medicine====\n[[File:Kircherears.jpg|thumb|right|The [[ear]]s of a human, cow, horse, dog, leopard, cat, rat, pig, sheep and goose illustrated in ''Musurgia Universalis''.]]\n\nKircher took a notably modern approach to the study of [[disease]]s, as early as 1646 using a [[microscope]] to investigate the [[blood]] of [[Black Death|plague]] victims. In his ''Scrutinium Pestis'' of 1658, he noted the presence of \"little worms\" or \"[[animalcules]]\" in the blood and concluded that the disease was caused by [[microorganism]]s. The conclusion was correct, although it is likely that what he saw were in fact [[red blood cell|red]] or [[white blood cell|white]] [[blood cell]]s and not the plague agent, ''[[Yersinia pestis]]''. He also proposed [[hygiene|hygienic]] measures to prevent the spread of disease, such as isolation, [[quarantine]], burning clothes worn by the infected and wearing [[Orthodontic headgear#Facemask and reverse-pull headgear|facemasks]] to prevent the inhalation of [[Microorganism|germ]]s.\n\n===Technology===\n[[File:Kirchermagneticclock.jpg|thumb|250px|Kircher's magnetic clock.]]\n\nIn 1646, Kircher published ''Ars Magna Lucis et Umbrae'', on the subject of the display of images on a screen using an apparatus similar to the [[magic lantern]] as developed by [[Christiaan Huygens]] and others. Kircher described the construction of a \"catastrophic lamp\" that used reflection to project images on the wall of a darkened room. Although Kircher did not invent the device, he made improvements over previous models, and suggested methods by which exhibitors could use his device. Much of the significance of his work arises from Kircher's rational approach towards the demystification of projected images.<ref>Musser, p 613</ref>\n\nPreviously such images had been used in Europe to mimic supernatural appearances (Kircher himself cites the use of displayed images by the rabbis in the court of [[King Solomon]]). Kircher stressed that exhibitors should take great care to inform spectators that such images were purely naturalistic, and not magical in origin.\n\nKircher also constructed a [[magnetism|magnetic]] clock, the mechanism of which he explained in his ''Magnes'' (1641). The device had originally been invented by another Jesuit, Fr. [[Linus of Liege]], and was described by an acquaintance of Line's in 1634. Kircher's patron Peiresc had claimed that the clock's motion supported the [[Copernican principle|Copernican]] cosmological model, the argument being that the magnetic sphere in the clock was caused to rotate by the magnetic force of the [[sun]].<ref name=\"Athanasius Kircher's Magnetic Clock\">[http://hotgates.stanford.edu/Eyes/kircher/intro.html Athanasius Kircher's Magnetic Clock] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816044854/http://hotgates.stanford.edu/Eyes/kircher/intro.html |date=August 16, 2010 }}, accessed 23 Apr 2011</ref>\n\nKircher's model disproved the hypothesis, showing that the motion could be produced by a [[water clock]] in the base of the device. Although Kircher wrote against the [[Heliocentrism|Copernican]] model in his ''Magnes'', supporting instead that of [[Tycho Brahe]], his later ''Itinerarium exstaticum'' (1656, revised 1671), presented several systems&nbsp;\u2014 including the Copernican&nbsp;\u2014 as distinct possibilities. The clock has been reconstructed by Caroline Bouguereau in collaboration with Michael John Gorman and is on display at the Green Library at Stanford University.<ref name=\"Athanasius Kircher's Magnetic Clock\"/>\n\nThe ''Musurgia Universalis'' (1650) sets out Kircher's views on [[music]]: he believed that the [[harmony]] of music reflected the proportions of the [[universe]]. The book includes plans for constructing water-powered [[automatic organ]]s, [[Musical notation|notations]] of [[bird vocalization|birdsong]] and diagrams of [[musical instrument]]s. One illustration shows the differences between the [[ear]]s of humans and other animals. In ''[[Phonurgia Nova]]'' (1673) Kircher considered the possibilities of transmitting music to remote places.\n\nOther machines designed by Kircher include an [[aeolian harp]], [[automaton]]s such as a statue which spoke and listened via a [[speaking tube]], a [[perpetual motion machine]], and a [[Katzenklavier]] (\"cat piano\"). The last of these would have driven spikes into the tails of cats, which would yowl to specified [[Pitch (music)|pitches]], although Kircher is not known to have actually constructed the instrument.\n\nIn ''Phonurgia Nova'', literally new methods of sound production, Kircher examined acoustic phenomena. He explores the use of horns and cones in amplifying sound with architectural applications. He also examines the phenomena of echoes in rooms with domes of different shapes including the muffling effect of an elliptical dome from Heidelberg. In one section he also explores the therapeutic effects of music especially in [[tarantism]], a theme from southern Italy.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1121/1.2992053|title=The 'Phonurgia Nova' of Athanasius Kircher: The Marvellous sound world of 17th century|pages=015002|series=Proceedings of Meetings on Acoustics|year=2008|last1=Tronchin|first1=Lamberto|first2=I.|last2= Durvilli |first3= V.|last3= Tarabusi}}</ref>\n\n===Combinatorics===\nAlthough Kircher's work was not mathematically based, he did develop various systems for generating and counting all combinations of a finite collection of objects (i.e., a finite [[Set theory|set]]), based on the previous work of [[Ramon Llull]]. His methods and diagrams are discussed in ''Ars Magna Sciendi, sive Combinatoria'', 1669. They include what may be the first recorded [[graph drawing|drawings]] of [[complete bipartite graph]]s, extending a similar technique used by Llull to visualize [[complete graph]]s.<ref>{{citation|contribution=Two thousand years of combinatorics|first=Donald E.|last=Knuth|authorlink=Donald Knuth|pages=7\u201337|title=Combinatorics: Ancient and Modern|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2013|editor1-first=Robin|editor1-last=Wilson|editor2-first=John J.|editor2-last=Watkins}}.\n</ref>  Kircher also employed combinatorics in his [[Arca Musarithmica]], an [[aleatoric music]] composition device capable of producing millions of church hymns by combining randomly selected musical phrases.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Turris Babel-Why the Tower Could Not Reach the Moon.jpg|thumb|''Turris Babel'': with typical eclecticism, Kircher illustrates the impossibility of the Tower of Babel having reached the moon, 1679]]\n\n===Scholarly influence===\nFor most of his professional life, Kircher was one of the scientific stars of his world: according to historian Paula Findlen, he was \"the first scholar with a global reputation\". His importance was twofold: to the results of his own [[experiment]]s and research he added information gleaned from his correspondence with over 760 scientists, physicians and above all his fellow Jesuits in all parts of the globe. The ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'' calls him a \"one-man intellectual clearing house\". His works, illustrated to his orders, were extremely popular, and he was the first scientist to be able to support himself through the sale of his books. His near-exact contemporary, the English philosopher-physician, [[Sir Thomas Browne]] (1605\u201382) collected his books avidly while his eldest son Edward Browne in 1665 visited the Jesuit priest resident at Rome. Towards the end of Kircher's life, however, his stock fell, as the [[rationalism|rationalist]] [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes|Cartesian]] approach began to dominate (Descartes himself described Kircher as \"more quacksalver than savant\").\n\n===Cultural legacy===\nKircher was largely neglected until the late 20th century. One writer attributes his rediscovery to the similarities between his eclectic approach and [[postmodernism]].\n\nAs few of Kircher's works have been translated, the contemporary emphasis has been on their [[aesthetic]] qualities rather than their actual content, and a succession of exhibitions have highlighted the beauty of their illustrations. Historian [[Anthony Grafton]] has said that \"the staggeringly strange dark continent of Kircher's work [is] the setting for a [[Borges]] story that was never written\", while [[Umberto Eco]] has written about Kircher in his novel ''[[The Island of the Day Before]]'', as well as in his non-fiction works ''[[The Search for the Perfect Language]]'' and ''[[Serendipities]]''. In ''Where Tigers Are At Home'', by [[Jean-Marie Blas de Robl\u00e8s]], the protagonist works on a  translation of a bogus 17th-century biography of  Kircher. The contemporary artist [[Cyb\u00e8le Varela]] has paid tribute to Kircher in her exhibition ''Ad Sidera per Athanasius Kircher'', held in the [[Collegio Romano]], in the same place where the [[Museum Kircherianum]] was.\n\nThe [[Museum of Jurassic Technology]] in [[Los Angeles]] has a hall dedicated to the life of Kircher. His ethnographic collection is in the [[Pigorini National Museum of Prehistory and Ethnography]] in Rome.\n\nJohn Glassie's book, ''[[A Man of Misconceptions]],'' traces connections between Kircher and figures such as [[Gianlorenzo Bernini]], [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]], and [[Isaac Newton]]. It also suggests influences on [[Edgar Allan Poe]], [[Franz Anton Mesmer]], [[Jules Verne]], and [[Marcel Duchamp]].\n\nIn the end, Glassie writes, Kircher should be acknowledged \u201cfor his effort to know everything and to share everything he knew, for asking a thousand questions about the world around him, and for getting so many others to ask questions about his answers; for stimulating, as well as confounding and inadvertently amusing, so many minds; for having been a source of so many ideas\u2014right, wrong, half-right, half-baked, ridiculous, beautiful, and all-encompassing.\u201d<ref>Glassie, p 272.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nKircher's life and research are central to the plot of [[James Rollins|James Rollin's]] 2015 novel ''The Bone Labyrinth''.\n\nHe is also mentioned in the Book of Life the 3rd book in the All Souls Trilogy by Deborah Harkness. \n\nHe further appears in two separate episodes in [[Daniel Kehlmann|Daniel Kehlmann's]] novel ''Tyll''.\n\nThe permanent exhibition ''The World Is Bound with Secret Knots'' at the [[Museum of Jurassic Technology]] is based on the life and work of Kircher. <ref>[http://mjt.org/exhibits/kircher/Knots.html Exhibition at the museum's website, retrieved July, 2019]</ref>\n\nHe is also a character (though largely off-stage, he is often mentioned by other characters) in the 'Ring of Fire' alternate history megaseries (published by Baen); in it, he was sent back to Germany in the early 1630s, where he became the unofficial pastor of the Catholic church in the temporally-transplanted town of Grantville, Thuringia-Franconia.\n\n<br />\n\n==Bibliography==\nKircher's principal works, in chronological order, are:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Link\n|-\n| 1631\n| ''[[Ars Magnesia]]''\n|\n|-\n| 1635\n| ''Primitiae gnomoniciae catroptricae''\n|\n|-\n| 1636\n| ''Prodromus coptus sive aegyptiacus''\n|\n|-\n| 1637\n| ''[[Specula Melitensis Encyclica]], hoc est syntagma novum instrumentorum physico- mathematicorum''\n|\n|-\n| 1641\n| ''Magnes sive de a